wn-positive-cases |archive-date=March 29, 2020 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 25,745\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 33,768\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 59,513\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 13.75%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | March 30, 2020<ref name=NYSstats-20200330>{{cite web |url=https://coronavirus.health.ny.gov/county-county-breakdown-positive-cases |title=County by County Breakdown of Positive Cases (Archived copy) |access-date=March 30, 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200330234014/https://coronavirus.health.ny.gov/county-county-breakdown-positive-cases |archive-date=March 30, 2020 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 29,044\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 37,453\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 66,497\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 11.74%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | March 31, 2020<ref name=NYSstats-20200331>{{cite web |url=https://coronavirus.health.ny.gov/county-county-breakdown-positive-cases |title=County by County Breakdown of Positive Cases (Archived copy) |access-date=March 31, 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200401033649/https://coronavirus.health.ny.gov/county-county-breakdown-positive-cases |archive-date=April 1, 2020 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 32,656\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 43,139\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 75,795\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 13.98%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | April 1, 2020<ref name=NYSstats-20200401>{{cite web |url=https://coronavirus.health.ny.gov/county-county-breakdown-positive-cases |title=County by County Breakdown of Positive Cases (Archived copy) |access-date=April 1, 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200401033649/https://coronavirus.health.ny.gov/county-county-breakdown-positive-cases |archive-date=April 1, 2020 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 36,273\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 47,439\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 83,712\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 10.44%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | April 2, 2020<ref name=\"NYSstats-20200402\">{{cite web|url=https://coronavirus.health.ny.gov/county-county-breakdown-positive-cases|title=County by County Breakdown of Positive Cases|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200403004044/https://coronavirus.health.ny.gov/county-county-breakdown-positive-cases|archive-date=April 2, 2020|access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 40,572\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 51,809\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 92,381\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 10.36%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | April 3, 2020<ref name=NYSstats-20200403>{{cite web |url=https://coronavirus.health.ny.gov/county-county-breakdown-positive-cases |title=County by County Breakdown of Positive Cases |access-date=April 2, 2020 |archive-url=https://coronavirus.health.ny.gov/county-county-breakdown-positive-cases |archive-date=April 3, 2020 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 45,704\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 57,159\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 102,863\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 11.35%\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Timeline of the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in New York (state)}}\n* [https://coronavirus.health.ny.gov/home Coronavirus information] from the [[New York State Department of Health]]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L8KAFVc5c_g&fbclid=IwAR127a7YzHdCWRodvUwfXHurNOlqDGooK70Y_UCALyl7X3C6WuuFtBV3n7k Times Square-New York City Walking Tour amid Coronavirus / COVID-19 Outbreak]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|New York]]\n[[Category:2020 in New York (state)|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Health in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:January 2020 events in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "Bosscube", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStatistics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_New_York_(state)"}
{"title_page": "\u00c9variste Kimba", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name\t\t\t= \u00c9variste Kimba\n|image\t\t\t= \u00c9varisteKimbaImage.jpg\n|caption                =\n\n|office1\t\t= Prime Minister of the [[Republic of the Congo (L\u00e9opoldville)|Republic of the Congo]]\n|term_start1\t\t= 13 October 1965\n|term_end1\t\t= 25 November 1965\n|president1\t\t= [[Joseph Kasa-Vubu]]\n|predecessor1\t\t= [[Moise Tshombe]]\n|successor1\t\t= [[L\u00e9onard Mulamba]]\n|office2\t\t= Minister of Foreign Affairs of the [[State of Katanga]]\n|term_start2\t\t= 1960\n|term_end2\t\t= January 1963\n|president2\t\t= Moise Tshombe\n|predecessor2\t\t= \n|successor2\t\t= \n|birth_date\t\t= 16 July 1926\n|birth_place\t\t= Nsaka, [[Bukama Territory]], [[Katanga Province]], [[Belgian Congo]]\n|death_date\t\t= 2 June 1966\n|death_place\t\t= [[Kinshasa|L\u00e9opoldville]], Democratic Republic of the Congo\n|party\t\t\t= [[CONAKAT|Conf\u00e9d\u00e9ration des associations tribales du Katanga]] (1958\u20131963)<br/>Association G\u00e9n\u00e9rale des Baluba du Katanga (1965)<br/>Front Democratique Congolais (1965)\n|spouse                 = Bernadette\n|children               = 4\n}}\n'''\u00c9variste Leon Kimba Mutombo''' (16 July 1926 \u2013 2 June 1966) was a Congolese journalist and politician who served as Foreign Minister of the [[State of Katanga]] from 1960 to 1963 and [[Prime Minister of the Democratic Republic of the Congo|Prime Minister]] of the [[Republic of the Congo (L\u00e9opoldville)|Democratic Republic of the Congo]] from 13 October to 25 November 1965. Kimba was born in 1926 in [[Katanga Province]], [[Belgian Congo]]. Following the completion of his studies he worked as a journalist and became editor-in-chief of the ''Essor du Congo''. In 1958 he and a group of Katangese concerned about domination of their province by people from the neighbouring [[Kasa\u00ef region]] founded the [[CONAKAT|Conf\u00e9d\u00e9ration des associations tribales du Katanga]] (CONAKAT), a regionalist political party. In 1960 the Congo became independent and shortly thereafter [[Moise Tshombe]] declared the secession of the [[State of Katanga]]. Kimba played an active role in the separatist state's government as its Minister of Foreign Affairs and participated in numerous talks with the central government aimed at political reconciliation. Following the collapse of the secession in early 1963, Kimba had a falling out with Tshombe and took up several ministerial posts in the new province of South Katanga.\n\nTshombe was later made Prime Minister of the Congo while Kimba joined the Association G\u00e9n\u00e9rale des Baluba du Katanga (BALUBAKAT) party. On 13 October 1965 [[President of the Democratic Republic of the Congo|President]] [[Joseph Kasa-Vubu]] dismissed Tshombe and appointed Kimba Prime Minister. Kimba formed a [[government of national unity]] and spent the following weeks attempting to achieve [[rapprochement]] between the Congo and other African states. However, his government failed to obtain a [[vote of confidence]] from [[Parliament of the Democratic Republic of the Congo|Parliament]], though Kasa-Vubu reappointed Kimba to the premiership in the face of determined opposition from Tshombe's supporters. On 25 November Army Commander-in-Chief [[Joseph-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Mobutu]] launched a coup removing both him and Kasa-Vubu from power and assumed control of the presidency. In May 1966 Mobutu's government accused Kimba of plotting with three other former government ministers to launch a coup. He was executed on 2 June for treason.\n\n==Early life==\n\u00c9variste Kimba was born on 16 July 1926 in the village of Nsaka, [[Bukama Territory]], [[Katanga Province]], [[Belgian Congo]].<ref name= nyt/>{{sfn|Gerard-Libois|Verhaegen|2015|p=353}} Ethnically, he was a member of [[Luba people|Luba]] tribe.<ref name= link>{{cite news| title = Congo: Kasavubu Acts| newspaper = Link| volume = 8| page = 28| date = 1965| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=CDZWAAAAYAAJ}}</ref> His father was a railway worker. He spent much of his youth in [[Lubumbashi|\u00c9lisabethville]], where he attended [[Catholic school|Roman Catholic schools]]. After receiving a basic primary and middle education Kimba, like his father, worked on the railroad, but continued his studies, taking night classes at St. Boniface Institute in sociology, law, and [[political economy]].<ref name= nyt/>{{sfn|Gerard-Libois|Verhaegen|2015|p=353}} He also played on the school's football team.<ref>{{cite news| title = Aide Reports Katanga Is Organizing Services| newspaper = The New York Times| page = 2| date = 15 October 1960}}</ref>\n\nKimba took up journalism in 1964 when he began writing for the ''Essor du Congo'' in \u00c9lisabethville.<ref name= lemonde>{{cite news| title = \u00c9VARISTE KIMBA un autre Katangais| newspaper = Le Monde| language = French| date = 15 October 1965| url = https://www.lemonde.fr/archives/article/1965/10/15/evariste-kimba-un-autre-katangais_2194072_1819218.html| access-date = 14 March 2020}}</ref> He later became the publication's [[editor-in-chief]].{{sfn|Gerard-Libois|Verhaegen|2015|p=353}} In 1960 he acted as vice president of the Association of the Congolese Press.{{sfn|Gerard-Libois|Verhaegen|2015|p=354}} He married a woman, Bernadette, and had four children with her.<ref name= nyt>{{cite news|title=Congo's New Premier: Evariste Leon Kimba|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1965/10/18/95912226.pdf|accessdate=21 August 2014|work=The New York Times|date=17 October 1965|page= 14}}</ref> In 1958 Kimba attended [[Expo 58]] in Belgium.<ref name= lemonde/> The following year he traveled abroad, visiting [[West Germany]], [[Northern Rhodesia]], [[Southern Rhodesia]], Senegal, the United States, Canada, France, Switzerland, Spain, Portugal, Italy, Greece, Ivory Coast, [[French Cameroon]], [[French Congo]], Chad, and [[French Madagascar]].{{sfn|Gerard-Libois|Verhaegen|2015|p=353}}\n\n==Political career==\n=== Early activities ===\nIn February 1957 Kimba and a group of other young Katangese concerned about domination of their province by people from the neighbouring [[Kasa\u00ef region]] met to discuss the political future of Katanga. In 1958 they founded the [[CONAKAT|Conf\u00e9d\u00e9ration des associations tribales du Katanga]] (CONAKAT), a regionalist political party.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|pp=236, 503}}\n\nIn the spring of 1960 [[Walter Ganshof van der Meersch]] was appointed the Belgian Minister of African Affairs and sent to the Congo to oversee its transition to independence.{{sfn|Kanza|1994|p=96}} Ganshof made Kimba his assistant chief of staff.{{sfn|Gerard-Libois|Verhaegen|2015|p=354}} On 12 June the Provincial Assembly of Katanga elected him to the [[Senate (Democratic Republic of the Congo)|Senate]] on a non-customary CONAKAT list.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|pp=325\u2013326}}{{sfn|Gerard-Libois|Verhaegen|2015|p=354}} On 16 June the Katangese provincial government was formed and Kimba was appointed Minister of Commerce and Industry.{{sfn|Gerard-Libois|Verhaegen|2015|p=354}} The [[Republic of the Congo (L\u00e9opoldville)|Republic of the Congo]] became independent on 30 June.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|p=328}}\n\n===Minister of Foreign Affairs of the State of Katanga===\nOn 11 July 1960 Katangese Provincial President [[Moise Tshombe]] declared the secession of the \"[[State of Katanga]]\".{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|pp=330, 333}} This was opposed by the regional Luba-dominated party, the Association G\u00e9n\u00e9rale des Baluba du Katanga (BALUBAKAT), but Kimba allied himself with Tshombe.<ref name= link/> Tshombe made Kimba Katanga's Minister of Foreign Affairs.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|p=331}} In December he accompanied Tshombe to a conference with leaders of the national Congolese government in [[Brazzaville]] to discuss political reconciliation. The talks dissolved without any tangible progress being achieved.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|p=364}} Though the role of the full Katangese government diminished over time under Tshombe's leadership, Kimba still actively met with Tshombe and held press conferences.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|p=377, 443}}\n\nIn April 1961 Kimba and Tshombe went to [[Mbandaka|Coquilhatville]] for further talks with the central government on political reconciliation and revising the constitution. Unhappy with the conference, Tshombe attempted to leave on 26 April, but he and Kimba were arrested and imprisoned for six weeks.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|p=382}} They were released on 22 June and allowed to return to Katanga.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|p=385}} In exchange for their liberation, the two men signed an agreement with the Congolese government declaring that representatives from Katangese constituencies would appear in the next session of Parliament. They later rejected the agreement.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|p=401}} In March and May 1962 the Katangese government held further talks with the central government in [[Kinshasa|L\u00e9opoldville]]. On 18 May the last round of negotiations was due to take place, but Tshombe, stalling for time, stayed in Katanga and sent Kimba in his place.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|p=462}} Under military pressure from the [[United Nations Operation in the Congo]], Tshombe declared the end of the Katangese secession in January 1963;{{sfn|O'Ballance|1999|p=63}} on 19 January he received UN officials at his residence and, in the presence of Kimba and some of his other ministers, declared that he would accept the UN's terms for Katanga's reintegration into the Congo.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|p=491}}\n\n=== Break from Tshombe ===\nIn the aftermath of the secession, Kimba had a falling out with Tshombe; Kimba preferred reconciliation with the central government, but Tshombe did not wish it at the time.<ref name= nyt/> Tshombe went to [[Paris]],<ref name= lukas/> while in February 1963 Kimba became Minister of Education of the new province of South Katanga. From April until August he served as the province's Minister of Economic Affairs and Minister of Information.{{sfn|Gerard-Libois|Verhaegen|2015|p=354}} In June he went to L\u00e9opoldville, the Congolese capital, to reach an understanding with the central government.<ref name= lukas>{{cite news| last = Lukas| first = J. Anthony| title = Katangese Asks for Congo Accord| newspaper = The New York Times| page = 6| date = 22 June 1963}}</ref> In September he attended a conference of moderate political parties in [[Kananga|Luluabourg]] as an observer. On 18 September Kimba went to Europe for \"health reasons\". He returned to the Congo in January 1964. On 13 December he was elected president of the central committee of the Entente Muluba, an \u00c9lisabethville-based organisation.{{sfn|Gerard-Libois|Verhaegen|2015|p=354}}\n\nThat year Tshombe was welcomed back into the country and made Prime Minister at the helm of a transitional government tasked with suppressing [[Simba rebellion|a leftist insurrection]] in the eastern Congo. After this was largely accomplished, [[1965 Democratic Republic of the Congo general election|general elections]] took place in 1965 and Tshombe's new coalition organisation, the [[Convention Nationale Congolaise]] (CONACO) won a majority of the seats in Parliament.{{sfn|Young|Turner|1985|pp=48\u201349}} Kimba also contested in the election for a seat in the [[National Assembly (Democratic Republic of the Congo)|Chamber of Deputies]], and won on a BALUBAKAT list. Afterwards he took a brief trip to Paris.{{sfn|Gerard-Libois|Verhaegen|2015|p=354}} Shortly before Parliament was due to reopen, the strength of CONACO faltered, and an anti-Tshombe coalition, the Front Democratique Congolais (FDC), was formed.<ref name= fdc>{{cite news| title = Tshombe Dismissed, Kimba New Premier| newspaper = Africa Diary| volume = 5| issue = 45| date = 1965| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=TVMOAQAAMAAJ}}</ref> Kimba joined it in October.{{sfn|Gerard-Libois|Verhaegen|2015|p=354}}\n\n=== Prime Minister of the Democratic Republic of the Congo ===\n[[File:Colonel Mobutu using a phone, 1960.jpg|thumb|Kimba was overthrown in a coup launched by [[Joseph-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Mobutu]] (pictured) in November 1965]]\nIn the months following the elections, the political rivalry between Tshombe and the President of the Congo, [[Joseph Kasa-Vubu]], grew increasingly tense. At the first session of the new Parliament on 13 October 1965, Kasa-Vubu unexpectedly announced that Tshombe's transitional government had fulfilled its purpose. He named Kimba the new Prime Minister and tasked him with forming a [[government of national unity]].{{sfn|Young|Turner|1985|pp=49\u201350}}<ref name= fdc/> Kimba had little personal following or national reputation and thus was considered inoffensive to members of Parliament and of little threat to Kasa-Vubu's ambitions. Kasa-Vubu also hoped that by appointing another Katangese to the post, he would avoid aggravating persisting secessionist sentiment in Katanga.<ref name= link/> Kimba's government was installed on 18 October,<ref>{{cite news| title = Kasavubu Installs New Congo Regime| newspaper = The New York Times| page = 12| date = 19 October 1965}}</ref> representing 16 of the 39 political parties with members in Parliament.{{sfn|Young|Turner|1985|p=51}}\n\nKimba's government was markedly less amicable towards Belgian interests than Tshombe's administration and more nationalistic,{{sfn|Gibbs|1991|p=162}} and aimed to curb Western influence in Congolese affairs.<ref name =AfricanWorld/> The new cabinet sought to improve the Congo's relations with active countries in the [[Organisation of African Unity]] including Ethiopia and Ghana, and to distance itself from the members of the [[African and Malagasy Union|African and Malagasy Common Organisation]].<ref name =AfricanWorld>{{cite news| title = Congo's \"National Unity\" Government: Mr. Tshombe a Likely Candidate for the Presidency| newspaper = African World| page = 15| date = December 1965| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=H4kXAQAAMAAJ}}</ref> The government opened negotiations with [[Republic of the Congo|Congo-Brazzaville]], and on 5 November Kimba announced that in its first step towards rehabilitating the Congo's ties with African states his government was renewing cross-river ferry traffic between Brazzaville and L\u00e9opoldville, which had been suspended for two years.<ref>{{cite news| title = Leopoldville Reopening Ferry to Brazzaville| newspaper = The New York Times| page = 2| date = 6 November 1965}}</ref> The following day he formally reestablished diplomatic relations with Congo-Brazzaville.{{sfn|O'Ballance|1999|p=90}}<ref>{{cite news| title = 2 Congos Resumes Ties After 2 Years| newspaper = The New York Times| page = 55| agency = United Press International| date = 7 November 1965}}</ref> He also reopened the Congo-Uganda border, which had been closed since February.{{sfn|O'Ballance|1999|p=90}} Kimba revised the composition of his government on 8 November.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|p=541}}\n\nTshombe's removal from power angered his supporters, and in the following weeks they competed with anti-Tshombe partisans for dominance in Parliament. On 14 November the Kimba Government was presented to the legislature for a formal [[vote of confidence]]. It was defeated, 72 to 76 in the Chamber of Deputies and 49 to 58 in the Senate.{{sfn|Young|Turner|1985|pp=50\u201351}} The next day Kasa-Vubu renominated Kimba as Prime Minister, resulting in a political deadlock.{{sfn|Young|Turner|1985|p=51}} On 25 November, Army Commander-in-Chief [[Joseph-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Mobutu]], who had previously supported Kimba, launched a coup removing both him and Kasa-Vubu from power and assumed control of the presidency.{{sfn|Young|Turner|1985|p=52}} Colonel [[L\u00e9onard Mulamba]] was appointed to replace Kimba.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|p=542}}\n\n==Arrest and death==\nIn May 1966 Kimba and former government ministers [[J\u00e9r\u00f4me Anany]], [[Emmanuel Bamba]], and [[Alexandre Mahamba]] were arrested by Mobutu's security forces while attending a meeting with military officials. They were taken to a military camp and tortured. Mobutu's regime accused them of plotting to assassinate Mobutu and Prime Minister Mulamba and overthrow the government. On 30 May the four men were tried before a [[military tribunal]]. The trial lasted an hour and a half and the accused were allowed no legal counsel.{{sfn|Ikambana|2006|p=56}} They pleaded innocence, claiming that they had been working at the behest of officers in the army. After deliberating for seven minutes, the three military judges found the four men guilty of treason and sentenced them to death.<ref>{{cite news| title = Death Sentence Given 4 Congo Ex-Officials: Former Premier, 3 Others Convicted and Doomed for Treason in 90-Minute Trial| newspaper = The Los Angeles Times| agency = [[United Press International]]| pages = 19| date = 1 June 1966}}</ref> This was in violation of standing Congolese law, which did not consider plotting a coup to be a [[capital crime]].{{sfn|Ikambana|2006|p=56}} On 2 June 1966, Kimba and the other men were publicly hanged in L\u00e9opoldville before a large crowd.<ref name= hanging>{{cite news|title=100,000 in Congo See Hanging of Ex-Premier and 3 Others|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1966/06/03/82445557.pdf|accessdate=21 August 2014|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=The New York Times|date=2 June 1966}}</ref> Kimba was the first of the four to be executed.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|p=546}} His family never received his body.{{sfn|Ikambana|2006|p=56}}\n\nKimba was the second former Prime Minister of the Congo to be killed after [[Patrice Lumumba]].<ref>{{cite news| last = Kirk| first = Russel| author-link = Russell Kirk| title = A Revolution's Victims| newspaper = The Los Angeles Times| page = B5| date = 9 June 1966}}</ref> Some time after Kimba's death, the Avenue des Chutes in Lubumbashi (formerly \u00c9lizabethville) was officially renamed in his honour, though the street is still usually referred to by its original name.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|p=664}} In 2011 a congress of the \"Luba People\" declared that Kimba was among \"our valiant martyrs\".{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|pp=603, 605}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book| last = Gerard-Libois| first = Jules| last2 = Verhaegen| first2 = Benoit| title = Congo 1965: Political Documents of a Developing Nation| publisher = Princeton University Press| edition = reprint| date = 2015| language = French| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=rBHWCgAAQBAJ&dq=| isbn = 9781400875436| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Gibbs| first = David N.| title = The Political Economy of Third World Intervention: Mines, Money, and U.S. Policy in the Congo Crisis| publisher = University of Chicago Press| series = American Politics and Political Economy| date = 1991| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=NgN64EXv8mgC&dq=| location = Chicago| isbn = 9780226290713| ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Ikambana| first = Jean-Louise Peta| title = Mobutu's Totalitarian Political System: An Afrocentric Analysis | publisher = Routledge| date = 2006| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=HeWRAgAAQBAJ&dq= | isbn = 9781135861513 | ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Kanza| first = Thomas R.| author-link = Thomas Kanza| title = The Rise and Fall of Patrice Lumumba: Conflict in the Congo| publisher = Schenkman Books, Inc.| edition = expanded| date = 1994| location = Rochester, Vermont| isbn = 0-87073-901-8| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=O'Ballance|first=Edgar|title=The Congo-Zaire Experience, 1960\u201398|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=vfCADAAAQBAJ&dq=|date=1999|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|location=Basingstoke|isbn=978-0-230-28648-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| editor-last = Omasombo Tshonda| editor-first = Jean| title = Haut-Katanga : Lorsque richesses \u00e9conomiques et pouvoirs politiques forcent une identit\u00e9 r\u00e9gionale| publisher = Mus\u00e9e royal de l\u2019Afrique centrale| volume = 1 |series = Provinces| date = 2018| location = Tervuren| language = French| url = http://www.africamuseum.be/sites/default/files/media/docs/research/publications/rmca/online/monographies-provinces/Haut-Katanga_Tome%201_WEB.pdf| isbn = 978-9-4926-6907-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Young| first = Crawford| last2 = Turner| first2 = Thomas Edwin| title = The Rise and Decline of the Zairian State| publisher = University of Wisconsin Press| date = 1985| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=R5pJxgosjIIC| isbn = 9780299101138| ref= harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{start box}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box|title=[[List of Prime ministers of the Democratic Republic of the Congo|Prime Minister of the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]|before=[[Moise Tshombe]]|after=[[L\u00e9onard Mulamba]]|years=13 October 1965 &nbsp;\u2013 25 November 1965}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DRCongoPMs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kimba, Evariste}}\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n[[Category:People of the Congo Crisis]]\n[[Category:People of the State of Katanga]]\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:1966 deaths]]\n[[Category:People executed by the Democratic Republic of the Congo by hanging]]\n[[Category:Executed Democratic Republic of the Congo people]]\n[[Category:20th-century executions by the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n[[Category:Executed prime ministers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Senate (Democratic Republic of the Congo)]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly (Democratic Republic of the Congo)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name\t\t\t= \u00c9variste Kimba\n|image\t\t\t= \u00c9varisteKimbaImage.jpg\n|caption                =\n\n|office1\t\t= Prime Minister of the [[Republic of the Congo (L\u00e9opoldville)|Republic of the Congo]]\n|term_start1\t\t= 13 October 1965\n|term_end1\t\t= 25 November 1965\n|president1\t\t= [[Joseph Kasa-Vubu]]\n|predecessor1\t\t= [[Moise Tshombe]]\n|successor1\t\t= [[L\u00e9onard Mulamba]]\n|office2\t\t= Minister of Foreign Affairs of the [[State of Katanga]]\n|term_start2\t\t= 1960\n|term_end2\t\t= January 1963\n|president2\t\t= Moise Tshombe\n|predecessor2\t\t= \n|successor2\t\t= \n|birth_date\t\t= 16 July 1926\n|birth_place\t\t= Nsaka, [[Bukama Territory]], [[Katanga Province]], [[Belgian Congo]]\n|death_date\t\t= 2 June 1966\n|death_place\t\t= [[Kinshasa|L\u00e9opoldville]], Democratic Republic of the Congo\n|party\t\t\t= [[CONAKAT|Conf\u00e9d\u00e9ration des associations tribales du Katanga]] (1958\u20131963)<br/>Association G\u00e9n\u00e9rale des Baluba du Katanga (1965)<br/>Front Democratique Congolais (1965)\n|spouse                 = Bernadette\n|children               = 4\n}}\n'''\u00c9variste Leon Kimba Mutombo''' (16 July 1926 \u2013 2 June 1966) was a Congolese journalist and politician who served as Foreign Minister of the [[State of Katanga]] from 1960 to 1963 and [[Prime Minister of the Democratic Republic of the Congo|Prime Minister]] of the [[Republic of the Congo (L\u00e9opoldville)|Democratic Republic of the Congo]] from 13 October to 25 November 1965. Kimba was born in 1926 in [[Katanga Province]], [[Belgian Congo]]. Following the completion of his studies he worked as a journalist and became editor-in-chief of the ''Essor du Congo''. In 1958 he and a group of Katangese concerned about domination of their province by people from the neighbouring [[Kasa\u00ef region]] founded the [[CONAKAT|Conf\u00e9d\u00e9ration des associations tribales du Katanga]] (CONAKAT), a regionalist political party. In 1960 the Congo became independent and shortly thereafter [[Moise Tshombe]] declared the secession of the [[State of Katanga]]. Kimba played an active role in the separatist state's government as its Minister of Foreign Affairs and participated in numerous talks with the central government aimed at political reconciliation. Following the collapse of the secession in early 1963, Kimba had a falling out with Tshombe and took up several ministerial posts in the new province of South Katanga.\n\nTshombe was later made Prime Minister of the Congo while Kimba joined the Association G\u00e9n\u00e9rale des Baluba du Katanga (BALUBAKAT) party. On 13 October 1965 [[President of the Democratic Republic of the Congo|President]] [[Joseph Kasa-Vubu]] dismissed Tshombe and appointed Kimba Prime Minister. Kimba formed a [[government of national unity]] and spent the following weeks attempting to achieve [[rapprochement]] between the Congo and other African states. However, his government failed to obtain a [[vote of confidence]] from [[Parliament of the Democratic Republic of the Congo|Parliament]], though Kasa-Vubu reappointed Kimba to the premiership in the face of determined opposition from Tshombe's supporters. On 25 November Army Commander-in-Chief [[Joseph-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Mobutu]] launched a coup removing both him and Kasa-Vubu from power and assumed control of the presidency. In May 1966 Mobutu's government accused Kimba of plotting with three other former government ministers to launch a coup. He was executed on 2 June for treason.\n\n==Early life==\n\u00c9variste Kimba was born on 16 July 1926, in the village of Nsaka, [[Bukama Territory]], [[Katanga Province]], [[Belgian Congo]].<ref name= nyt/>{{sfn|Gerard-Libois|Verhaegen|2015|p=353}} Ethnically, he was a member of [[Luba people|Luba]] tribe.<ref name= link>{{cite news| title = Congo: Kasavubu Acts| newspaper = Link| volume = 8| page = 28| date = 1965| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=CDZWAAAAYAAJ}}</ref> His father was a railway worker. He spent much of his youth in [[Lubumbashi|\u00c9lisabethville]], where he attended [[Catholic school|Roman Catholic schools]]. After receiving a basic primary and middle education Kimba, like his father, worked on the railroad, but continued his studies, taking night classes at St. Boniface Institute in sociology, law, and [[political economy]].<ref name= nyt/>{{sfn|Gerard-Libois|Verhaegen|2015|p=353}} He also played on the school's football team.<ref>{{cite news| title = Aide Reports Katanga Is Organizing Services| newspaper = The New York Times| page = 2| date = 15 October 1960}}</ref>\n\nKimba took up journalism in 1964 when he began writing for the ''Essor du Congo'' in \u00c9lisabethville.<ref name= lemonde>{{cite news| title = \u00c9VARISTE KIMBA un autre Katangais| newspaper = Le Monde| language = French| date = 15 October 1965| url = https://www.lemonde.fr/archives/article/1965/10/15/evariste-kimba-un-autre-katangais_2194072_1819218.html| access-date = 14 March 2020}}</ref> He later became the publication's [[editor-in-chief]].{{sfn|Gerard-Libois|Verhaegen|2015|p=353}} In 1960 he acted as vice president of the Association of the Congolese Press.{{sfn|Gerard-Libois|Verhaegen|2015|p=354}} He married a woman, Bernadette, and had four children with her.<ref name= nyt>{{cite news|title=Congo's New Premier: Evariste Leon Kimba|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1965/10/18/95912226.pdf|accessdate=21 August 2014|work=The New York Times|date=17 October 1965|page= 14}}</ref> In 1958 Kimba attended [[Expo 58]] in Belgium.<ref name= lemonde/> The following year he traveled abroad, visiting [[West Germany]], [[Northern Rhodesia]], [[Southern Rhodesia]], Senegal, the United States, Canada, France, Switzerland, Spain, Portugal, Italy, Greece, Ivory Coast, [[French Cameroon]], [[French Congo]], Chad, and [[French Madagascar]].{{sfn|Gerard-Libois|Verhaegen|2015|p=353}}\n\n==Political career==\n=== Early activities ===\nIn February 1957 Kimba and a group of other young Katangese concerned about domination of their province by people from the neighbouring [[Kasa\u00ef region]] met to discuss the political future of Katanga. In 1958 they founded the [[CONAKAT|Conf\u00e9d\u00e9ration des associations tribales du Katanga]] (CONAKAT), a regionalist political party.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|pp=236, 503}}\n\nIn the spring of 1960 [[Walter Ganshof van der Meersch]] was appointed the Belgian Minister of African Affairs and sent to the Congo to oversee its transition to independence.{{sfn|Kanza|1994|p=96}} Ganshof made Kimba his assistant chief of staff.{{sfn|Gerard-Libois|Verhaegen|2015|p=354}} On 12 June the Provincial Assembly of Katanga elected him to the [[Senate (Democratic Republic of the Congo)|Senate]] on a non-customary CONAKAT list.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|pp=325\u2013326}}{{sfn|Gerard-Libois|Verhaegen|2015|p=354}} On 16 June the Katangese provincial government was formed and Kimba was appointed Minister of Commerce and Industry.{{sfn|Gerard-Libois|Verhaegen|2015|p=354}} The [[Republic of the Congo (L\u00e9opoldville)|Republic of the Congo]] became independent on 30 June.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|p=328}}\n\n===Minister of Foreign Affairs of the State of Katanga===\nOn 11 July 1960 Katangese Provincial President [[Moise Tshombe]] declared the secession of the \"[[State of Katanga]]\".{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|pp=330, 333}} This was opposed by the regional Luba-dominated party, the Association G\u00e9n\u00e9rale des Baluba du Katanga (BALUBAKAT), but Kimba allied himself with Tshombe.<ref name= link/> Tshombe made Kimba Katanga's Minister of Foreign Affairs.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|p=331}} In December he accompanied Tshombe to a conference with leaders of the national Congolese government in [[Brazzaville]] to discuss political reconciliation. The talks dissolved without any tangible progress being achieved.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|p=364}} Though the role of the full Katangese government diminished over time under Tshombe's leadership, Kimba still actively met with Tshombe and held press conferences.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|p=377, 443}}\n\nIn April 1961 Kimba and Tshombe went to [[Mbandaka|Coquilhatville]] for further talks with the central government on political reconciliation and revising the constitution. Unhappy with the conference, Tshombe attempted to leave on 26 April, but he and Kimba were arrested and imprisoned for six weeks.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|p=382}} They were released on 22 June and allowed to return to Katanga.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|p=385}} In exchange for their liberation, the two men signed an agreement with the Congolese government declaring that representatives from Katangese constituencies would appear in the next session of Parliament. They later rejected the agreement.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|p=401}} In March and May 1962 the Katangese government held further talks with the central government in [[Kinshasa|L\u00e9opoldville]]. On 18 May the last round of negotiations was due to take place, but Tshombe, stalling for time, stayed in Katanga and sent Kimba in his place.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|p=462}} Under military pressure from the [[United Nations Operation in the Congo]], Tshombe declared the end of the Katangese secession in January 1963;{{sfn|O'Ballance|1999|p=63}} on 19 January he received UN officials at his residence and, in the presence of Kimba and some of his other ministers, declared that he would accept the UN's terms for Katanga's reintegration into the Congo.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|p=491}}\n\n=== Break from Tshombe ===\nIn the aftermath of the secession, Kimba had a falling out with Tshombe; Kimba preferred reconciliation with the central government, but Tshombe did not wish it at the time.<ref name= nyt/> Tshombe went to [[Paris]],<ref name= lukas/> while in February 1963 Kimba became Minister of Education of the new province of South Katanga. From April until August he served as the province's Minister of Economic Affairs and Minister of Information.{{sfn|Gerard-Libois|Verhaegen|2015|p=354}} In June he went to L\u00e9opoldville, the Congolese capital, to reach an understanding with the central government.<ref name= lukas>{{cite news| last = Lukas| first = J. Anthony| title = Katangese Asks for Congo Accord| newspaper = The New York Times| page = 6| date = 22 June 1963}}</ref> In September he attended a conference of moderate political parties in [[Kananga|Luluabourg]] as an observer. On 18 September Kimba went to Europe for \"health reasons\". He returned to the Congo in January 1964. On 13 December he was elected president of the central committee of the Entente Muluba, an \u00c9lisabethville-based organisation.{{sfn|Gerard-Libois|Verhaegen|2015|p=354}}\n\nThat year Tshombe was welcomed back into the country and made Prime Minister at the helm of a transitional government tasked with suppressing [[Simba rebellion|a leftist insurrection]] in the eastern Congo. After this was largely accomplished, [[1965 Democratic Republic of the Congo general election|general elections]] took place in 1965 and Tshombe's new coalition organisation, the [[Convention Nationale Congolaise]] (CONACO) won a majority of the seats in Parliament.{{sfn|Young|Turner|1985|pp=48\u201349}} Kimba also contested in the election for a seat in the [[National Assembly (Democratic Republic of the Congo)|Chamber of Deputies]], and won on a BALUBAKAT list. Afterwards he took a brief trip to Paris.{{sfn|Gerard-Libois|Verhaegen|2015|p=354}} Shortly before Parliament was due to reopen, the strength of CONACO faltered, and an anti-Tshombe coalition, the Front Democratique Congolais (FDC), was formed.<ref name= fdc>{{cite news| title = Tshombe Dismissed, Kimba New Premier| newspaper = Africa Diary| volume = 5| issue = 45| date = 1965| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=TVMOAQAAMAAJ}}</ref> Kimba joined it in October.{{sfn|Gerard-Libois|Verhaegen|2015|p=354}}\n\n=== Prime Minister of the Democratic Republic of the Congo ===\n[[File:Colonel Mobutu using a phone, 1960.jpg|thumb|Kimba was overthrown in a coup launched by [[Joseph-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Mobutu]] (pictured) in November 1965]]\nIn the months following the elections, the political rivalry between Tshombe and the President of the Congo, [[Joseph Kasa-Vubu]], grew increasingly tense. At the first session of the new Parliament on 13 October 1965, Kasa-Vubu unexpectedly announced that Tshombe's transitional government had fulfilled its purpose. He named Kimba the new Prime Minister and tasked him with forming a [[government of national unity]].{{sfn|Young|Turner|1985|pp=49\u201350}}<ref name= fdc/> Kimba had little personal following or national reputation and thus was considered inoffensive to members of Parliament and of little threat to Kasa-Vubu's ambitions. Kasa-Vubu also hoped that by appointing another Katangese to the post, he would avoid aggravating persisting secessionist sentiment in Katanga.<ref name= link/> Kimba's government was installed on 18 October,<ref>{{cite news| title = Kasavubu Installs New Congo Regime| newspaper = The New York Times| page = 12| date = 19 October 1965}}</ref> representing 16 of the 39 political parties with members in Parliament.{{sfn|Young|Turner|1985|p=51}}\n\nKimba's government was markedly less amicable towards Belgian interests than Tshombe's administration and more nationalistic,{{sfn|Gibbs|1991|p=162}} and aimed to curb Western influence in Congolese affairs.<ref name =AfricanWorld/> The new cabinet sought to improve the Congo's relations with active countries in the [[Organisation of African Unity]] including Ethiopia and Ghana, and to distance itself from the members of the [[African and Malagasy Union|African and Malagasy Common Organisation]].<ref name =AfricanWorld>{{cite news| title = Congo's \"National Unity\" Government: Mr. Tshombe a Likely Candidate for the Presidency| newspaper = African World| page = 15| date = December 1965| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=H4kXAQAAMAAJ}}</ref> The government opened negotiations with [[Republic of the Congo|Congo-Brazzaville]], and on 5 November Kimba announced that in its first step towards rehabilitating the Congo's ties with African states his government was renewing cross-river ferry traffic between Brazzaville and L\u00e9opoldville, which had been suspended for two years.<ref>{{cite news| title = Leopoldville Reopening Ferry to Brazzaville| newspaper = The New York Times| page = 2| date = 6 November 1965}}</ref> The following day he formally reestablished diplomatic relations with Congo-Brazzaville.{{sfn|O'Ballance|1999|p=90}}<ref>{{cite news| title = 2 Congos Resumes Ties After 2 Years| newspaper = The New York Times| page = 55| agency = United Press International| date = 7 November 1965}}</ref> He also reopened the Congo-Uganda border, which had been closed since February.{{sfn|O'Ballance|1999|p=90}} Kimba revised the composition of his government on 8 November.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|p=541}}\n\nTshombe's removal from power angered his supporters, and in the following weeks they competed with anti-Tshombe partisans for dominance in Parliament. On 14 November the Kimba Government was presented to the legislature for a formal [[vote of confidence]]. It was defeated, 72 to 76 in the Chamber of Deputies and 49 to 58 in the Senate.{{sfn|Young|Turner|1985|pp=50\u201351}} The next day Kasa-Vubu renominated Kimba as Prime Minister, resulting in a political deadlock.{{sfn|Young|Turner|1985|p=51}} On 25 November, Army Commander-in-Chief [[Joseph-D\u00e9sir\u00e9 Mobutu]], who had previously supported Kimba, launched a coup removing both him and Kasa-Vubu from power and assumed control of the presidency.{{sfn|Young|Turner|1985|p=52}} Colonel [[L\u00e9onard Mulamba]] was appointed to replace Kimba.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|p=542}}\n\n==Arrest and death==\nIn May 1966 Kimba and former government ministers [[J\u00e9r\u00f4me Anany]], [[Emmanuel Bamba]], and [[Alexandre Mahamba]] were arrested by Mobutu's security forces while attending a meeting with military officials. They were taken to a military camp and tortured. Mobutu's regime accused them of plotting to assassinate Mobutu and Prime Minister Mulamba and overthrow the government. On 30 May the four men were tried before a [[military tribunal]]. The trial lasted an hour and a half and the accused were allowed no legal counsel.{{sfn|Ikambana|2006|p=56}} They pleaded innocence, claiming that they had been working at the behest of officers in the army. After deliberating for seven minutes, the three military judges found the four men guilty of treason and sentenced them to death.<ref>{{cite news| title = Death Sentence Given 4 Congo Ex-Officials: Former Premier, 3 Others Convicted and Doomed for Treason in 90-Minute Trial| newspaper = The Los Angeles Times| agency = [[United Press International]]| pages = 19| date = 1 June 1966}}</ref> This was in violation of standing Congolese law, which did not consider plotting a coup to be a [[capital crime]].{{sfn|Ikambana|2006|p=56}} On 2 June 1966, Kimba and the other men were publicly hanged in L\u00e9opoldville before a large crowd.<ref name= hanging>{{cite news|title=100,000 in Congo See Hanging of Ex-Premier and 3 Others|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1966/06/03/82445557.pdf|accessdate=21 August 2014|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=The New York Times|date=2 June 1966}}</ref> Kimba was the first of the four to be executed.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|p=546}} His family never received his body.{{sfn|Ikambana|2006|p=56}}\n\nKimba was the second former Prime Minister of the Congo to be killed after [[Patrice Lumumba]].<ref>{{cite news| last = Kirk| first = Russel| author-link = Russell Kirk| title = A Revolution's Victims| newspaper = The Los Angeles Times| page = B5| date = 9 June 1966}}</ref> Some time after Kimba's death, the Avenue des Chutes in Lubumbashi (formerly \u00c9lizabethville) was officially renamed in his honour, though the street is still usually referred to by its original name.{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|p=664}} In 2011 a congress of the \"Luba People\" declared that Kimba was among \"our valiant martyrs\".{{sfn|Omasombo Tshonda|2018|pp=603, 605}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book| last = Gerard-Libois| first = Jules| last2 = Verhaegen| first2 = Benoit| title = Congo 1965: Political Documents of a Developing Nation| publisher = Princeton University Press| edition = reprint| date = 2015| language = French| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=rBHWCgAAQBAJ&dq=| isbn = 9781400875436| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Gibbs| first = David N.| title = The Political Economy of Third World Intervention: Mines, Money, and U.S. Policy in the Congo Crisis| publisher = University of Chicago Press| series = American Politics and Political Economy| date = 1991| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=NgN64EXv8mgC&dq=| location = Chicago| isbn = 9780226290713| ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Ikambana| first = Jean-Louise Peta| title = Mobutu's Totalitarian Political System: An Afrocentric Analysis | publisher = Routledge| date = 2006| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=HeWRAgAAQBAJ&dq= | isbn = 9781135861513 | ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Kanza| first = Thomas R.| author-link = Thomas Kanza| title = The Rise and Fall of Patrice Lumumba: Conflict in the Congo| publisher = Schenkman Books, Inc.| edition = expanded| date = 1994| location = Rochester, Vermont| isbn = 0-87073-901-8| ref = harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=O'Ballance|first=Edgar|title=The Congo-Zaire Experience, 1960\u201398|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=vfCADAAAQBAJ&dq=|date=1999|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|location=Basingstoke|isbn=978-0-230-28648-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| editor-last = Omasombo Tshonda| editor-first = Jean| title = Haut-Katanga : Lorsque richesses \u00e9conomiques et pouvoirs politiques forcent une identit\u00e9 r\u00e9gionale| publisher = Mus\u00e9e royal de l\u2019Afrique centrale| volume = 1 |series = Provinces| date = 2018| location = Tervuren| language = French| url = http://www.africamuseum.be/sites/default/files/media/docs/research/publications/rmca/online/monographies-provinces/Haut-Katanga_Tome%201_WEB.pdf| isbn = 978-9-4926-6907-0|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book| last = Young| first = Crawford| last2 = Turner| first2 = Thomas Edwin| title = The Rise and Decline of the Zairian State| publisher = University of Wisconsin Press| date = 1985| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=R5pJxgosjIIC| isbn = 9780299101138| ref= harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{start box}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box|title=[[List of Prime ministers of the Democratic Republic of the Congo|Prime Minister of the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]|before=[[Moise Tshombe]]|after=[[L\u00e9onard Mulamba]]|years=13 October 1965 &nbsp;\u2013 25 November 1965}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DRCongoPMs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kimba, Evariste}}\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n[[Category:People of the Congo Crisis]]\n[[Category:People of the State of Katanga]]\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:1966 deaths]]\n[[Category:People executed by the Democratic Republic of the Congo by hanging]]\n[[Category:Executed Democratic Republic of the Congo people]]\n[[Category:20th-century executions by the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]\n[[Category:Executed prime ministers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Senate (Democratic Republic of the Congo)]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly (Democratic Republic of the Congo)]]\n", "name_user": "Indy beetle", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89variste_Kimba"}
{"title_page": "Garret Ahearn", "text_new": "{{short description|Irish politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Seanad \u00c9ireann|Senator]]\n| name         = Garret Ahearn\n| image        = \n| office       = [[Seanad \u00c9ireann|Senator]]\n| term_start   = April 2020\n| term_end     =   \n| constituency = [[Administrative Panel]]\n| birth_name   =\n| birth_date   = \n| birth_place  = \n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| nationality  = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n| party        = \n| spouse       =   \n| children     =   \n| education    =\n| alma_mater   = \n| website      =\n}}\n'''Garret Ahearn''' is an Irish [[Fine Gael]] politician who has been a [[Seanad \u00c9ireann|Senator]] for the [[Administrative Panel]] since April 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=Seanad general election 2020 |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/elections/seanad-general-election-2020/#panels |website=www.oireachtas.ie |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\nHe was formerly a member of [[Tipperary County Council]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Clonmel Borough District |url=https://www.tipperarycoco.ie/your-council/clonmel-borough-district |website=www.tipperarycoco.ie |publisher=Tipperary County Council |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External Links==\n[https://www.finegael.ie/our-people/councillors/tipperary/clonmel/garret-ahearn/ Garret Ahearn on Fine Gael Website]\n\n{{Members of the 26th Seanad}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Fine Gael senators]]\n[[Category:Members of the 26th Seanad]]\n[[Category:People from County Tipperary]]\n[[Category:Local councillors in County Tipperary]]\n\n{{FineGael-politician-stub}}\n{{Ireland-senator-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Irish politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Seanad \u00c9ireann|Senator]]\n| name         = Garret Ahearn\n| image        = \n| office       = [[Seanad \u00c9ireann|Senator]]\n| term_start   = April 2020\n| term_end     =   \n| constituency = [[Administrative Panel]]\n| birth_name   =\n| birth_date   = \n| birth_place  = \n| death_date   =\n| death_place  =\n| nationality  = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n| party        = \n| spouse       =   \n| children     =   \n| education    =\n| alma_mater   = \n| website      =\n}}\n'''Garret Ahearn''' is an Irish [[Fine Gael]] politician who has been a [[Seanad \u00c9ireann|Senator]] for the [[Administrative Panel]] since April 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=Seanad general election 2020 |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/elections/seanad-general-election-2020/#panels |website=www.oireachtas.ie |publisher=Oireachtas |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\nHe was formerly a member of [[Tipperary County Council]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Clonmel Borough District |url=https://www.tipperarycoco.ie/your-council/clonmel-borough-district |website=www.tipperarycoco.ie |publisher=Tipperary County Council |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External Links==\n[https://www.finegael.ie/our-people/councillors/tipperary/clonmel/garret-ahearn/ Garret Ahearne on Fine Gael Website]\n\n{{Members of the 26th Seanad}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Fine Gael senators]]\n[[Category:Members of the 26th Seanad]]\n[[Category:People from County Tipperary]]\n[[Category:Local councillors in County Tipperary]]\n\n{{FineGael-politician-stub}}\n{{Ireland-senator-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Joseywales1961", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo fixed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Garret_Ahearn"}
{"title_page": "Erias Lukwago", "text_new": "{{short description|Ugandan lawyer and politician}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name   = Erias Lukwago\n| image = \n| image_size     = \n| caption  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1970|5|11|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Uganda]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place =\n| alma_mater         =[[Makerere University]]<br/> {{small|([[Bachelor of Laws]])}}<br/>[[Law Development Centre]]<br/>{{small|([[Legal practice|Diploma in Legal Practice]])}}\n| occupation     = Lawyer, politician\n| years_active              = 1998 \u2014 present\n| nationality               = [[Uganda]]n\n| citizenship               = [[Uganda]]\n| residence                 = [[Kampala]], [[Uganda]]\n| known_for                 = [[Politics]], [[Law]]\n| networth                  = \n| home_town                 = [[Kampala]]\n| title                     = [[Lord Mayor]] of [[Kampala]]\n| children                  = 6\n}}\n\n'''Erias Lukwago Ssalongo''' (born 11 May 1970), is a [[Uganda]]n [[lawyer]] and [[politician]]. He is the  [[Lord Mayor]] of the city of [[Kampala]], the capital of [[Uganda]] and the largest metropolitan area in the country. He was elected to that position on 14 January 2011.<ref>{{cite web\n |title=How Erias Lukwago Won Kampala Vote \n |url=http://www.newvision.co.ug/D/8/12/749174 \n |date=15 March 2011 \n |last=Francis Kagolo \n |first=and Patrick Ogwang \n |newspaper=[[New Vision]] (Kampala) \n |access-date=6 February 2015 \n |url-status=dead \n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206210008/http://www.newvision.co.ug/D/8/12/749174 \n |archive-date=6 February 2015 \n |df= \n}}</ref> He was voted out of office on 25 November 2013 by Councillors after a tribunal found him guilty of incompetence and abuse of office. The [[Kampala Capital City Authority]] councilors voted 29 to three to impeach him.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-25086200|date=25 November 2013|accessdate=6 February 2015|last=BBC News|publisher=[[BBC News]] (London)|title=Kampala Mayor Erias Lukwago Ousted By Councillors}}</ref> He was re-instated on 28 November 2013 after the High Court Judge Yasin Nyanzi ordered Kampala Minister [[Frank Tumwebaze]] to stop the implementation of the tribunal report that paved way for his censure.<ref>{{cite web|\nurl=http://www.africareview.com/News/Court-reinstates-embattled-Kampala-mayor/-/979180/2092640/-/evm6x2z/-/index.htm|title=Court Reinstates Embattled Kampala Lord Mayor|date=29 November 2013|\naccessdate=6 February 2015|first=Anthony|last=Wesaka|\nnewspaper=[[Nation Media Group|Africa Review]] (Nairobi)}}</ref>\n\n==Background and education== \nHe was born in Kabungo Masaka district (now Kalungu district) on 11 May 1970 to Muhamoud Mirundi and Salimanti Nakayaga. Lukwago is reported to have more than twenty siblings.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/SpecialReports/Elections/-/859108/1125760/-/k3ov4q/-/index.html | title=Lukwago - A Politician of All Seasons | date=16 March 2011 | accessdate=6 February 2015 | last=Don Wanyama | first=and Mercy Nalugo | newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] (Kampala)}}</ref> Lukwago attended [[Makerere University]] between 1995 until 1997, graduating with a [[Bachelor of Laws]] degree. He went on to obtain a [[Law practice|Diploma in Legal Practice]] from the [[Law Development Center]] in 1998. He also holds a Certificate in Advocacy Skills from the [[International Law Institute]].\n\n==Work experience==\nSince 1998, Lukwago has worked as the [[Partner (business rank)|managing partner]] in the offices of Lukwago and Co. Advocates, a [[Kampala]] law firm that specializes in [[constitutional law]] and [[human rights law]]. In 2005, he was elected to the [[Parliament of Uganda|Ugandan Parliament]], on the Democratic Party ticket, representing the [[Kampala|Central Kampala Constituency]]. While in parliament, he served on the Legal and Parliamentary Affairs Committee and  on the Local Government Accounts Committee. He resigned from Parliament in 2011 and was elected [[Lord Mayor]] of the [[Kampala|City of Kampala]]. Lukwago has in the past served as national legal adviser to the Democratic Party in [[Uganda]], and as [[Shadow Minister]] for Justice and Constitutional Affairs.<ref>[http://www.parliament.go.ug/index.php?option=com_wrapper&Itemid=37 Work History of Erias Lukwago]</ref> On 20 May 2011, Lukwago was sworn in as Lord Mayor of Kampala for a five-year term.<ref>{{cite web\n |title=Lukwago Swears In As Lord Mayor \n |url=http://www.newvision.co.ug/D/8/12/755266 \n |date=21 May 2011 \n |access-date=6 February 2015 \n |newspaper=[[New Vision]] (Kampala) \n |first=John \n |last=Semakula \n |url-status=dead \n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207050630/http://www.newvision.co.ug/D/8/12/755266 \n |archive-date=7 February 2015 \n |df= \n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201105191386.html|title=Uganda: Lord Mayor, Councillors Swear Today|last=Mulondo|first=Emmanuel|date=2011-05-19|work=The Monitor (Kampala)|access-date=2017-11-23}}</ref> In 2016 he was sworn in for his second term\n\n==Personal details==\nErias Lukwago is married to Zawedde Lubwama Lukwago and they have six children. He has in the past been a member of the Democratic Party in Uganda, although in the 2011 elections he ran as an independent.<ref>{{cite web | accessdate=6 February 2015 |  url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201103160026.html | date=16 March 2011 | newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] via [[AllAfrica.com]] | title=Uganda: DP's Mao Congratulates New Mayor}}</ref> He belongs to the Nkima Clan of Buganda.{{Citation needed|date=March 2016}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Kampala Capital City Authority]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://allafrica.com/stories/201103160027.html How the City Mayoral Seat Was Won In 2011]\n* [http://allafrica.com/stories/201103160038.html Kampala: What New City Executives Will Do]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bef | before =[[Nasser Sebaggala]]<br/><small>As Mayor of Kampala</small>}}\n{{s-ttl | title =Lord Mayor of Kampala|years=2011 - 2016}}\n{{s-aft | after =Incumbent|years= 2011 - Present}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lukwago, Erias}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Kampala]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Uganda]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party (Uganda) politicians]]\n[[Category:Ugandan activists]]\n[[Category:Ugandan lawyers]]\n[[Category:Makerere University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Kampala District]]\n[[Category:Ganda people]]\n[[Category:Law Development Centre alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ugandan lawyer and politician}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name   = Erias Lukwago\n| image = \n| image_size     = \n| caption  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1970|5|11|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Uganda]]\n| death_date  = \n| death_place =\n| alma_mater         =[[Makerere University]]<br/> {{small|([[Bachelor of Laws]])}}<br/>[[Law Development Centre]]<br/>{{small|([[Legal practice|Diploma in Legal Practice]])}}\n| occupation     = Lawyer, politician\n| years_active              = 1998 \u2014 present\n| nationality               = [[Uganda]]n\n| citizenship               = [[Uganda]]\n| residence                 = [[Kampala]], [[Uganda]]\n| known_for                 = [[Politics]], [[Law]]\n| networth                  = \n| home_town                 = [[Kampala]]\n| title                     = [[Lord Mayor]] of [[Kampala]]\n| children                  = 6\n}}\n\n'''Erias Lukwago Ssalongo''' (born 11 May 1970), is a [[Uganda]]n [[lawyer]] and [[politician]]. He is the  [[Lord Mayor]] of the city of [[Kampala]], the capital of [[Uganda]] and the largest metropolitan area in the country. He was elected to that position on 14 January 2011.<ref>{{cite web\n |title=How Erias Lukwago Won Kampala Vote \n |url=http://www.newvision.co.ug/D/8/12/749174 \n |date=15 March 2011 \n |last=Francis Kagolo \n |first=and Patrick Ogwang \n |newspaper=[[New Vision]] (Kampala) \n |access-date=6 February 2015 \n |url-status=dead \n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206210008/http://www.newvision.co.ug/D/8/12/749174 \n |archive-date=6 February 2015 \n |df= \n}}</ref> He was voted out of office on 25 November 2013 by Councillors after a tribunal found him guilty of incompetence and abuse of office. The [[Kampala Capital City Authority]] councilors voted 29 to three to impeach him.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-25086200|date=25 November 2013|accessdate=6 February 2015|last=BBC News|publisher=[[BBC News]] (London)|title=Kampala Mayor Erias Lukwago Ousted By Councillors}}</ref> He was re-instated on 28 November 2013 after the High Court Judge Yasin Nyanzi ordered Kampala Minister [[Frank Tumwebaze]] to stop the implementation of the tribunal report that paved way for his censure.<ref>{{cite web|\nurl=http://www.africareview.com/News/Court-reinstates-embattled-Kampala-mayor/-/979180/2092640/-/evm6x2z/-/index.htm|title=Court Reinstates Embattled Kampala Lord Mayor|date=29 November 2013|\naccessdate=6 February 2015|first=Anthony|last=Wesaka|\nnewspaper=[[Nation Media Group|Africa Review]] (Nairobi)}}</ref>\n\n==Background and education== \nHe was born in Kabungo Masaka district(now Kalungu district) on 11 May 1970 to Muhamoud Mirundi and Salimanti Nakayaga. Lukwago is reported to have more than twenty siblings.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/SpecialReports/Elections/-/859108/1125760/-/k3ov4q/-/index.html | title=Lukwago - A Politician of All Seasons | date=16 March 2011 | accessdate=6 February 2015 | last=Don Wanyama | first=and Mercy Nalugo | newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] (Kampala)}}</ref> Lukwago attended [[Makerere University]] between 1995 until 1997, graduating with a [[Bachelor of Laws]] degree. He went on to obtain a [[Law practice|Diploma in Legal Practice]] from the [[Law Development Center]] in 1998. He also holds a Certificate in Advocacy Skills from the [[International Law Institute]].\n\n==Work experience==\nSince 1998, Lukwago has worked as the [[Partner (business rank)|managing partner]] in the offices of Lukwago and Co. Advocates, a [[Kampala]] law firm that specializes in [[constitutional law]] and [[human rights law]]. In 2005, he was elected to the [[Parliament of Uganda|Ugandan Parliament]], on the Democratic Party ticket, representing the [[Kampala|Central Kampala Constituency]]. While in parliament, he served on the Legal and Parliamentary Affairs Committee and  on the Local Government Accounts Committee. He resigned from Parliament in 2011 and was elected [[Lord Mayor]] of the [[Kampala|City of Kampala]]. Lukwago has in the past served as national legal adviser to the Democratic Party in [[Uganda]], and as [[Shadow Minister]] for Justice and Constitutional Affairs.<ref>[http://www.parliament.go.ug/index.php?option=com_wrapper&Itemid=37 Work History of Erias Lukwago]</ref> On 20 May 2011, Lukwago was sworn in as Lord Mayor of Kampala for a five-year term.<ref>{{cite web\n |title=Lukwago Swears In As Lord Mayor \n |url=http://www.newvision.co.ug/D/8/12/755266 \n |date=21 May 2011 \n |access-date=6 February 2015 \n |newspaper=[[New Vision]] (Kampala) \n |first=John \n |last=Semakula \n |url-status=dead \n |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207050630/http://www.newvision.co.ug/D/8/12/755266 \n |archive-date=7 February 2015 \n |df= \n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201105191386.html|title=Uganda: Lord Mayor, Councillors Swear Today|last=Mulondo|first=Emmanuel|date=2011-05-19|work=The Monitor (Kampala)|access-date=2017-11-23}}</ref> In 2016 he was sworn in for his second term\n\n==Personal details==\nErias Lukwago is married to Zawedde Lubwama Lukwago and they have six children. He has in the past been a member of the Democratic Party in Uganda, although in the 2011 elections he ran as an independent.<ref>{{cite web | accessdate=6 February 2015 |  url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201103160026.html | date=16 March 2011 | newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] via [[AllAfrica.com]] | title=Uganda: DP's Mao Congratulates New Mayor}}</ref> He belongs to the Nkima Clan of Buganda.{{Citation needed|date=March 2016}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Kampala Capital City Authority]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://allafrica.com/stories/201103160027.html How the City Mayoral Seat Was Won In 2011]\n* [http://allafrica.com/stories/201103160038.html Kampala: What New City Executives Will Do]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bef | before =[[Nasser Sebaggala]]<br/><small>As Mayor of Kampala</small>}}\n{{s-ttl | title =Lord Mayor of Kampala|years=2011 - 2016}}\n{{s-aft | after =Incumbent|years= 2011 - Present}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lukwago, Erias}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Kampala]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Uganda]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party (Uganda) politicians]]\n[[Category:Ugandan activists]]\n[[Category:Ugandan lawyers]]\n[[Category:Makerere University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Kampala District]]\n[[Category:Ganda people]]\n[[Category:Law Development Centre alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Strickesel", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed a typo found byWikipedia:Typo Team/moss\u2013 you can help!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erias_Lukwago"}
{"title_page": "Gympie", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2012}}\n{{Infobox Australian place\n| type         = town\n| name         = Gympie\n| state        = qld\n| image        =Gympie Town Hall, 2015.jpg\n| caption      =Gympie Town Hall, 2015 \n| postcode     = 4570\n| coordinates  = {{coord|-26.19|152.6655|type:city_region:AU-QLD|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_label_position = left\n| pop          = 21599\n| pop_year     = 2018\n| pop_footnotes = <ref name=ABSSUA/>\n| poprank      =\n| density      =\n| est          = 1867\n| area         = 69.3\n| area_footnotes =  <ref name=\"ABSSUAProf\">{{cite web|title=2011 Census Community Profiles: Gympie|url=http://www.censusdata.abs.gov.au/census_services/getproduct/census/2011/communityprofile/3007|website=ABS Census|publisher=[[Australian Bureau of Statistics]]|accessdate=15 September 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419161356/http://www.censusdata.abs.gov.au/census_services/getproduct/census/2011/communityprofile/3007|archivedate=19 April 2018}}</ref> (2011 urban)\n| lga          = [[Gympie Region]]\n| stategov     = [[Electoral district of Gympie|Gympie]]\n| fedgov       = [[Division of Wide Bay|Wide Bay]]\n| dist1        = 160\n| location1    = Brisbane\n| mintemp      = 13.6\n| maxtemp      = 27.1\n| rainfall     = 1132.9\n| near-n              = [[Araluen, Queensland|Araluen]]\n| near-ne             = [[Victory Heights, Queensland|Victory Heights]]\n| near-e              = [[Victory Heights, Queensland|Victory Heights]]\n| near-se             = [[Monkland, Queensland|Monkland]]\n| near-s              = [[Monkland, Queensland|Monkland]]\n| near-sw             = [[Southside, Queensland|Southside]]\n| near-w              = [[Widgee Crossing North, Queensland|Widgee Crossing North]]\n| near-nw             = [[Two Mile, Queensland|Two Mile]]\n}}\n\n'''Gympie''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0261|\u026a|m|p|i}}<ref>''[[Macquarie Dictionary|Macquarie Dictionary, Fourth Edition]]'' (2005). Melbourne, The Macquarie Library Pty Ltd. {{ISBN|1-876429-14-3}}</ref> is a town and a [[Suburbs and localities (Australia)|locality]] in the [[Gympie Region]], [[Queensland]], Australia.<ref name=qpnt>{{cite QPN|15149|Gympie|town in Gympie Region|accessdate=6 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=qpnl>{{cite QPN|46339|Gympie|locality in Gympie Region|accessdate=6 November 2017}}</ref> Located in the [[Wide Bay-Burnett]] district, Gympie is about {{convert|160|km|mi|-1}} north of the state capital, [[Brisbane]]. The city lies on the [[Mary River (Queensland)|Mary River]], which floods the town periodically.  Gympie is the administrative centre for the [[Gympie Region]] area. As at June 2018 Gympie had a population of 21,599.<ref name=ABSSUA>{{cite web|title=3218.0 \u2013 Regional Population Growth, Australia, 2017\u201318: Population Estimates by Significant Urban Area, 2008 to 2018|url=http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/DetailsPage/3218.02017-18|website=Australian Bureau of Statistics|publisher=[[Australian Bureau of Statistics]]|date=27 March 2019|accessdate=25 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327110730/http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/DetailsPage/3218.02017-18|archive-date=27 March 2019|url-status=live}} Estimated resident population, 30 June 2018.</ref>\n\nGympie is famous for its gold field.<ref name=\"ewg\">{{cite book |title=Encyclopedia of World Geography |last=Khan |first=M. Ali |author2=A.Balakishan |year=2007 |publisher=Sarup & Sons |isbn=8176257737 |page=45 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s-HoFag2kDcC |accessdate=20 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629121324/https://books.google.com/books?id=s-HoFag2kDcC |archive-date=29 June 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> It contains a number of historic buildings registered on the [[Queensland Heritage Register]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Plan of Leases and Claims on the Deep Lead, Gympie, 1869.jpg|left|thumb|Map of gold mining leases and claims on the Deep Lead, 1869]]\n''[[Gabi-Gabi language|Gubbi Gubbi]] (Kabi Kabi, Cabbee, Carbi, Gabi Gabi)'' is an [[Australian Aboriginal language]] formerly spoken by the indigenous peoples of the [[Sunshine Coast Region]] and [[Gympie Region]], particularly the towns of Caloundra, [[Noosa Heads, Queensland|Noosa Heads]], Gympie and extending north towards [[Maryborough, Queensland|Maryborough]] and south to [[Caboolture, Queensland|Caboolture]]''.<ref>{{Cite SLQ-CC-BY|url=https://maps.slq.qld.gov.au/iyil/view/13|title=Gubbi Gubbi|website=Queensland Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander languages map|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref>''\n\nGympie's name derives from the [[Gabi-Gabi language|Gubbi Gubbi]] word ''gimpi-gimpi'', which means \"stinging tree\"<ref name=\"his1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gympie.qld.gov.au/categoryholder.asp?CategoryID=3 |title=History |publisher=Gympie Regional Council |accessdate=20 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317135422/http://www.gympie.qld.gov.au/categoryholder.asp?CategoryID=3 |archivedate=17 March 2012}}</ref> and refers to ''[[Dendrocnide moroides]]''. The tree has large, round leaves that have similar properties to [[stinging nettles]]. The town was previously named '''Nashville''', after [[James Nash (prospector)|James Nash]], who discovered gold in the area in 1867.<ref>Hon. C. Wallace, [http://www.cabinet.qld.gov.au/MMS/StatementDisplaySingle.aspx?id=56070 Gympie residents have chance to make their mark on the map] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716094658/http://www.cabinet.qld.gov.au/MMS/StatementDisplaySingle.aspx?id=56070 |date=16 July 2011 }}, 14 January 2008. Accessed 18 April 2009.</ref> The name was changed to Gympie in 1868.<ref>{{Cite web| author1=Unidentified | title=Gympie Fire Station in 1955 | publication-date=1955 | publisher=John Oxley Library, State Library of Queensland | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/36936554 | accessdate=20 April 2018 }}</ref>[[File:Gympie Hospital, 1891.png|thumb|left|Gympie Hospital, 1891]]Graziers were the original European settlers.  Subsequently, James Nash reported the discovery of 'payable' alluvial gold on 16 October 1867.<ref name=\"adbnash\">Stoodley, June. [http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/nash-james-4286/text6935 Nash, James (1834\u20131913)] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20120509030557/http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/nash-james-4286/text6935 |date=9 May 2012 }}. Australian Dictionary of Biography, National Centre of Biography. Australian National University.</ref> At the time of Nash's discovery, Queensland was suffering from a severe economic depression.  Nash probably saved Queensland from bankruptcy. A memorial fountain in Gympie's Park honours Nash's discovery.<ref name=\"adbnash\" /> The Gympie Gold Rush Festival celebrates the event today.  The Gold Rush Festival holds 10 days of cultural events in October.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://goldrush.org.au/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=484&Itemid=124|title=Gold Rush Festival \u2013 Gympie Goldrush|website=goldrush.org.au|accessdate=19 April 2018}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> [[Gold mining]] still plays a role in the area's fortunes, along with agriculture (dairy predominantly), timber and tourism.  The gold rush's rapid development led to streets that are in an irregular fashion.<ref name=\"heritage\" />[[File:StateLibQld 1 231369 View of Gympie's streets, ca. 1925.jpg|thumb|left|Lower Mary Street, c.1925]]\n\nGympie Creek Post Office opened on 1 December 1867. It was renamed Gympie in 1868.<ref name=\"Post Office\">{{Cite web  | last = Premier Postal History  | title = Post Office List  | publisher = Premier Postal Auctions  | url = https://www.premierpostal.com/cgi-bin/wsProd.sh/Viewpocdwrapper.p?SortBy=QLD&country=  | accessdate = 10 May 2014  | url-status = live  | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140515223132/http://www.premierpostal.com/cgi-bin/wsProd.sh/Viewpocdwrapper.p?SortBy=QLD&country=  | archivedate = 15 May 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThe railway from Maryborough completed in 1881.<ref name=\"heritage\">{{Cite book |title=Heritage Trails of the Great South East |last=[[Environmental Protection Agency (Queensland)|Environmental Protection Agency]] |year=2000 |publisher=State of Queensland |isbn=0-7345-1008-X |pages=90, 148 }}</ref> The [[North Coast railway line, Queensland#First connection|North Coast railway]] linked Gympie to Brisbane in 1891.<ref name=\"heritage\"/> A fire brigade was in operation in 1900. The state declared Gympie a town in 1903.  A powdered milk factory began operations in 1953.\n\n===Flooding===\n[[File:The Gympie flood, June 19 1873 - 31256978480.jpg|left|thumb|1873 Gympie flood]]\nSignificant floods along the Mary River have caused inundations of the town in 1870, 1873, 1893, 1955, 1968, 1974, [[1989 Gympie, Southern Queensland & Eastern New South Wales Floods|1989]], 1992, [[1999 Gympie - Maryborough, Queensland Floods|1999]], [[2010\u20132011 Queensland floods|2011]]<ref name=\"bommajflood\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bom.gov.au/hydro/flood/qld/brochures/mary/mary.shtml#PreviousFlooding |title=Flood Warning System for the Mary River |publisher=Bureau of Meteorology |accessdate=6 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421120408/http://www.bom.gov.au/hydro/flood/qld/brochures/mary/mary.shtml#PreviousFlooding |archive-date=21 April 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> and [[2013 Eastern Australia floods#Queensland|2013]]. The first recorded flood in Gympie was in [[1870 Maryborough - Gympie, Queensland Floods|1870]].  Most of the floods occur between December and April and are typically caused by heavy rainfall in the headwaters to the south.<ref name=\"mmq\" />\n\nThe highest flood ever recorded in Gympie occurred on 2 February 1893 when the river peaked at 25.45&nbsp;m.<ref name=\"mmq\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.gympietimes.com.au/story/2010/03/06/mary-mary-quite-contrary/ |title=Mary, Mary quite contrary |author=Jannette Parke |accessdate=6 May 2012 |date=6 March 2010 |newspaper=[[The Gympie Times]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100311054714/http://www.gympietimes.com.au/story/2010/03/06/mary-mary-quite-contrary/ |archivedate=11 March 2010}}</ref> Gympie was declared a natural disaster area during the 1999 floods.<ref name=\"qfc\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.weeklytimesnow.com.au/article/2011/01/10/279851_latest-news.html |title=Qld flood crisis hits Gympie |accessdate=6 May 2012 |date=10 January 2011 |work=The Weekly Times|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120508060206/http://www.weeklytimesnow.com.au/article/2011/01/10/279851_latest-news.html |archivedate=8 May 2012}}</ref> The river peaked at 21.9&nbsp;m then.\n\nNumerous highways and roads in and around the town which were destroyed or damaged during floods in 2011 was repaired under Operation Queenslander,<ref name=\"rfr\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.gympietimes.com.au/story/2012/05/07/road-flood-repairs-on-going/ |title=Road flood repairs on-going |accessdate=20 May 2012 |date=7 May 2012 |work=[[The Gympie Times]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120518064846/http://www.gympietimes.com.au/story/2012/05/07/road-flood-repairs-on-going/ |archivedate=18 May 2012}}</ref> the name given to post-flood reconstruction efforts in Queensland.\n\nIn March 2012, the [[Gympie Regional Council]] decided to spend about $30,000 for a [[cost benefit analysis]] on flood mitigation measures.<ref name=\"staf\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/story/2012/03/09/staying-afloat-we-dont-have-to-drown/ |title=Staying afloat |accessdate=6 May 2012 |date=9 March 2012 |newspaper=Sunshine Coast Daily |publisher=Sunshine Coast Newspaper Company }}</ref>\n\n== Heritage listings ==\n[[File:Gympie Court House.jpg|thumb|Gympie Court House, 2012]]\nGympie has a number of [[heritage-listed]] sites, including:\n* Brisbane Road: [[Monkland State School Residence]]<ref>{{cite QHR|16749|Monkland State School Residence|602013|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 2 Caledonian Hill: [[Gympie Town Hall]]<ref>{{cite QHR|28821|Gympie Town Hall Reserve Complex|602789|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* Channon Street: [[Gympie Court House]]<ref>{{cite QHR|15308|Gympie Court House|600533|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* Channon Street: [[Old Gympie Post Office]]<ref>{{cite QHR|15309|My Country; Old Post Office|600534|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* Channon Street: [[Surface Hill Uniting Church]]<ref>{{cite QHR|16292|Surface Hill Uniting Church|601529|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 26 Channon Street: [[Gympie Lands Office]]<ref>{{cite QHR|20029|Gympie Court House and Lands Office (former)|602778|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* cnr Channon Street and Nash Streets: former [[Queensland National Bank, Gympie|Queensland National Bank]]<ref>{{cite QHR|20026|Queensland National Bank (former)|602773|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* Church Street: [[St Patricks Church, Gympie|St Patricks Church]]<ref>{{cite QHR|16266|St Patricks Church|601503|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 17 Crown Road: former [[Gympie Ambulance Station]]<ref>{{cite QHR|32244|Gympie Ambulance Station (former)|602794|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* Mary Street: [[Gympie and Widgee War Memorial Gates]]<ref>{{cite QHR|15310|Gympie and Widgee War Memorial Gates|600535|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 199 Mary Street: former [[Royal Bank of Queensland, Gympie|Royal Bank of Queensland]]<ref>{{cite QHR|20093|Royal Bank of Queensland (former)|602774|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 216 Mary Street: former [[Crawford and Co Building]]<ref>{{cite QHR|20097|Crawford and Co. Building (former)|602780|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 218 Mary Street: [[Tozer's Building]]<ref>{{cite QHR|20098|Tozer's Building|602779|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 235 Mary Street: [[Smithfield Chambers]]<ref>{{cite QHR|20102|Smithfield Chambers|602777|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 236 Mary Street: former [[Australian Joint Stock Bank, Gympie|Australian Joint Stock Bank]] and former [[Gympie Stock Exchange]] offices & club<ref>{{cite QHR|20103|Australian Joint Stock Bank (former)/Gympie Stock Exchange Offices and Club (former)|602772|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 242 Mary Street: former [[Bank of New South Wales, Gympie|Bank of New South Wales]]<ref>{{cite QHR|20104|Bank of New South Wales (former)|602775|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 39 Nash Street: [[Gympie School of Arts]]<ref>{{cite QHR|16646|Gympie School of Arts|601910|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* River Road: [[Gympie Memorial Park]]<ref>{{cite QHR|31071|Memorial Park|602729|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 1 Station Road: [[Railway Hotel, Gympie|Railway Hotel]]<ref>{{cite QHR|19662|Railway Hotel|602540|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* Tozer Street: [[Gympie railway station]]<ref>{{cite QHR|16772|Gympie Railway Station Platform Complex|602036|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Population==\nAccording to the [[2016 Australian census|2016 census]] of Population, there 20,966 people in Gympie.\n* Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people made up 3.9% of the population. \n* 82.4% of people were born in Australia. The next most common countries of birth were England 2.6%, New Zealand 1.9% and Philippines 0.6%.   \n* 89.6% of people spoke only English at home. \n* The most common responses for religion were No Religion 30.1%, Catholic 16.8% and Anglican 15.6%.<ref name=ABSSUACensus16>{{Census 2016 AUS|id=3007|name=Gympie (Significant Urban Area)|accessdate=24 March 2019|quick=on}}[[File:CC-BY icon.svg|50px]] Material was copied from this source, which is available under a [https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/ Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171016050101/https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/ |date=16 October 2017 }}.</ref>\n\n==Climate==\nGympie has a [[humid subtropical climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]]: '''Cfa''').\n\n<br />\n{{Weather box\n|location = Gympie (1870\u20132019)\n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n|Jan record high C = 42.4\n|Feb record high C = 41.3\n|Mar record high C = 38.1\n|Apr record high C = 35.6\n|May record high C = 32.8\n|Jun record high C = 29.2\n|Jul record high C = 30.2\n|Aug record high C = 34.3\n|Sep record high C = 38.2\n|Oct record high C = 40.1\n|Nov record high C = 42.2\n|Dec record high C = 42.0\n|year record high C = 42.4 \n|Jan high C = 31.3\n|Feb high C = 30.4\n|Mar high C = 29.3\n|Apr high C = 27.3\n|May high C = 24.5\n|Jun high C = 22.1\n|Jul high C = 21.9\n|Aug high C = 23.4\n|Sep high C = 26.1\n|Oct high C = 28.3\n|Nov high C = 30.2\n|Dec high C = 31.3\n|year high C = 27.2\n|Jan low C = 19.6\n|Feb low C = 19.7\n|Mar low C = 18.2\n|Apr low C = 14.7\n|May low C = 10.8\n|Jun low C = 8.0 \n|Jul low C = 6.3\n|Aug low C = 7.1\n|Sep low C = 10.3\n|Oct low C = 13.8\n|Nov low C = 16.5\n|Dec low C = 18.6\n|year low C = 13.6\n|Jan record low C = 12.0\n|Feb record low C = 12.3\n|Mar record low C = 9.8\n|Apr record low C = 3.6\n|May record low C = -0.9\n|Jun record low C = -3.3\n|Jul record low C = -4.3\n|Aug record low C = -1.8\n|Sep record low C = 1.3\n|Oct record low C = 4.6\n|Nov record low C = 3.5\n|Dec record low C = 10.1\n|year record low C = -4.3\n|Jan rain mm = 161.9\n|Feb rain mm = 167.3\n|Mar rain mm = 144.7\n|Apr rain mm = 82.9\n|May rain mm = 71.4\n|Jun rain mm = 60.2\n|Jul rain mm = 51.3\n|Aug rain mm = 40.0\n|Sep rain mm = 45.0\n|Oct rain mm = 72.0\n|Nov rain mm = 87.5\n|Dec rain mm = 136.6 \n|Jan rain days = 12.8\n|Feb rain days = 13.6\n|Mar rain days = 14.4\n|Apr rain days = 11.5\n|May rain days = 10.3\n|Jun rain days = 8.3\n|Jul rain days = 6.9\n|Aug rain days = 6.4\n|Sep rain days = 6.7\n|Oct rain days = 8.2\n|Nov rain days = 9.5\n|Dec rain days = 11.2\n|unit rain days = 0.2mm\n|source 1 = [[Bureau of Meteorology (Australia)|Bureau of Meteorology]]<ref>{{BoM Aust stats|site_ref=cw_040093_All|site_name=Gympie|accessdate=23 March 2013|date=March 2013}}</ref>\n|date=June 2015}}\n\n==Attractions==\n[[File:Rattler Hero 1.jpg|alt=|thumb|The Mary Valley Rattler C17 Locomotive 967]]\nThe Gympie Gold Mining and Historical Museum houses memorabilia from the early gold mining era, as well as displays showcasing military, rural, transport, communications, and steam development in Australia.  The WoodWorks Museum provides an insight into the timber industry and social history of yesteryear through displays and demonstrations. Features include a large selection of pioneering hand tools, a 1925 Republic truck, bullock wagons, and a blacksmith shop.\n\nThe [[Mary Valley Rattler|Valley Rattler]] steam train is a tourist train that began operations in 1996. It follows the Mary River through the forests and plantations of the Mary Valley to [[Dagun, Queensland|Dagun]].<ref name=\"qpmv\">{{cite web |url=http://queenslandplaces.com.au/node/4888 |title=Mary Valley |work=Queensland Places |publisher=Centre for the Government of Queensland, University of Queensland. |accessdate=20 May 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025043958/http://queenslandplaces.com.au/node/4888 |archivedate=25 October 2012}}</ref> The train departs and returns to the [[Gympie railway station|Old Gympie Railway Station]] in Tozer Street, an original railway station from the 1900s gold rush.\n\nApproximately 25 km south of Gympie, the town of Amamoor hosts the annual National Country Music Muster. Held over six days and nights in August in the [[Amamoor Forest Reserve]],<ref name=\"asf\">{{cite web |url=http://www.derm.qld.gov.au/parks/amamoor/camping.html |title=Amamoor State Forest and Forest Reserve \u2013 Camping information |publisher=Department of Environment and Resource Management |date=14 October 2011 |accessdate=20 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120509195323/http://www.derm.qld.gov.au/parks/amamoor/camping.html |archivedate=9 May 2012}}</ref> the Muster is the largest outdoor country music festival in Australia.\n\nGympie's Mary St offers a wide array of bars, cafes, and shops with 19th Century Victorian architecture. The historic Railway Hotel was built in 1915 and is listed on the [[Queensland Heritage Register]].<ref name=\"poh\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.gympietimes.com.au/story/2012/01/17/piece-of-history-goes-on-the-block/ |title=Piece of history goes on the block |author=Lee Gailer |accessdate=6 May 2012 |date=17 January 2012 |newspaper=[[The Gympie Times]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120202054912/http://www.gympietimes.com.au/story/2012/01/17/piece-of-history-goes-on-the-block/ |archivedate=2 February 2012}}</ref> The Gympie Town Hall Reserve Complex, built in 1890, was added to the Queensland Heritage Register in 2011.<ref name=\"shl\">{{cite web |url=http://www.qldheritage.org.au/state-heritage-listing-for-gympie-icon.html |title=State heritage listing for Gympie icon |date=9 September 2012 |publisher=Queensland Heritage Council |accessdate=21 May 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130329021958/http://www.qldheritage.org.au/state-heritage-listing-for-gympie-icon.html |archivedate=29 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Mothar Mountain Speedway]] is Gympie's local raceway which hosts the motorsport Speedway A.K.A [[dirt track racing]]. Mothar Mountain Speedway is promoted by the Gympie Saloon Car Club Ltd.\n \nThe annual [[Heart of Gold International Short Film Festival]] is held in Gympie in March.[[File:Big Pineapple, Gympie, Queensland.jpg|thumb|[[Australia's big things|Big Pineapple]], Gympie (now removed)|alt=]]\n\n24 km south-east of Gympie, [[Woondum National Park]] provides access to subtropical rainforest, creeks and granite outcrops.<ref name=\"wnp\">{{cite web |url=http://www.derm.qld.gov.au/parks/woondum/index.html |title=Woondum National Park |date=9 June 2011 |publisher=Department of Environment and Resource Management |accessdate=21 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120505053817/http://www.derm.qld.gov.au/parks/woondum/index.html |archivedate=5 May 2012}}</ref> Facilities include picnic tables, barbecues, firewood, fresh water, amenities, and bush-walking tracks. Access is by dirt road and a high-clearance vehicle is recommended.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/story/2010/03/24/trip-mothar-mountain-rock-pools/ |title=Trip to Mothar Mountain rock pools |author=Alexia Purcell |accessdate=21 May 2012 |date=24 March 2010 |newspaper=Sunshine Coast Daily |publisher=Sunshine Coast Newspaper Company }}</ref>\n\nAbout 30 minutes' drive east of Gympie is [[Tin Can Bay]], where one can hand-feed [[Indo-Pacific hump-backed dolphin]]s. The feeding is regulated for the protection of the dolphins.  \n\nGympie and the surrounding area is part of the [[Great Sandy Biosphere Reserve]], listed by [[UNESCO]] as a world conservation site.\n\nThe [[Gympie Pyramid]] is also a minor attraction.\n\n[[Gympie Cemetery]] crawls are run by the Gympie Family History Society.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gympiefhs.egympie.com.au/Cemetery%20Crawls.htm |title=Cemetery Crawls |publisher=Gympie Family History Society Inc. |accessdate=19 March 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160229184008/http://www.gympiefhs.egympie.com.au/Cemetery%20Crawls.htm |archivedate=29 February 2016}}</ref> Participants learn about the town's pioneering families.\n\n==Education==\nGympie has many schools, reflecting its importance as a regional service centre. State primary schools include:\n* Gympie West State School opened on 28 January 1958.<ref name=\"qs\">{{Cite QldSchool|accessdate=18 April 2019}}</ref>\n* Chatsworth State School opened on 18 April 1900.<ref name=qs/>\n* Monkland State School opened on 24 September 1884.<ref name=qs/>\n* Jones Hill State School opened on 29 January 1902.<ref name=qs/>\n* Gympie Central State School opened on 18 October 1869.<ref name=qs/>\n* Two Mile State School opened on 9 July 1883.<ref name=\"qfhs\"/> \n* One Mile State School was the first school opened in Gympie on 20 September 1869 as One Mile Boys State School with the One Mile Girls and Infants State School opening in October 1874. In January 1943, they were merged into One Mile State School.<ref name=\"qfhs\">{{Citation|title=Queensland schools past and present|publication-date=2010|author1=Queensland Family History Society|edition=Version 1.01|publisher=[[Queensland Family History Society]]|isbn=978-1-921171-26-0}}</ref> \n* Gympie East State School opened on 25 January 1965.<ref name=qs/>\n* Gympie South State School opened on 4 July 1910.<ref name=qs/>\n\nState secondary schools include:\n* [[James Nash State High School]] opened on 24 January 1977.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jamesnashshs.eq.edu.au/Pages/default.aspx|title=James Nash SHS|access-date=29 January 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202060858/https://jamesnashshs.eq.edu.au/Pages/default.aspx|archivedate=2 February 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"qs\"/>\n* [[Gympie State High School]] opened on 29 January 1912.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gympieshs.eq.edu.au/Pages/default.aspx|title=Gympie SHS|access-date=29 January 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204054453/https://gympieshs.eq.edu.au/Pages/default.aspx|archivedate=4 February 2017}}</ref> This school is one of the oldest state secondary schools in Queensland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://education.qld.gov.au/library/edhistory/topics/oldest-sec-schools.html|title=The oldest state secondary schools in Queensland|website=education.qld.gov.au|language=en-AU|access-date=29 January 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180129140634/http://education.qld.gov.au/library/edhistory/topics/oldest-sec-schools.html|archivedate=29 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nPrivate schools offer both primary and secondary education.  They include Victory College, [[Cooloola Christian College]] and [[St Patrick's College, Gympie|St Patrick's]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gympie.qld.gov.au/schools_list.asp|title=Gympie Regional Council \u2013 Schools|accessdate=19 April 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090518203212/http://www.gympie.qld.gov.au/schools_list.asp|archivedate=18 May 2009}}</ref> St Patrick's College in Gympie opened on 30 December 1916.<ref name=qs/>\n\nGympie is home to one campus of the [[Wide Bay Institute of TAFE]] located on Cartwright Road.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.widebay.tafe.qld.gov.au/about_us/campuses/gympie.html |title=Gympie |publisher=Wide Bay Institute of TAFE |accessdate=20 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320173302/http://widebay.tafe.qld.gov.au/about_us/campuses/gympie.html |archivedate=20 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe University of the Sunshine Coast (USC) has a campus in Gympie located on Cartwright Road. This campus offers undergraduate study in primary education, nursing, business, and commerce.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usc.edu.au/learn/the-usc-experience/study-locations/study-in-gympie|title=USC Gympie|website=www.usc.edu.au|accessdate=19 April 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803235403/http://www.usc.edu.au/learn/the-usc-experience/study-locations/study-in-gympie|archivedate=3 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Amenities ==\nThe [[Gympie Regional Council]] operates a public library at 8\u201314 Mellor Street.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gympie.qld.gov.au/web/library/library-locations|title=Library locations|website=[[Gympie Regional Council]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180131023219/https://www.gympie.qld.gov.au/web/library/library-locations|archive-date=31 January 2018|url-status=live|access-date=31 January 2018}}</ref> It opened in 1995.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.plconnect.slq.qld.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0012/388497/SLQ_StatsBulletin1617_20171109.pdf|title=Public Libraries Statistical Bulletin 2016\u201317|date=November 2017|website=Public Libraries Connect|publisher=[[State Library of Queensland]]|page=13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180130022546/http://www.plconnect.slq.qld.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0012/388497/SLQ_StatsBulletin1617_20171109.pdf|archive-date=30 January 2018|url-status=live|access-date=30 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Gympie branch of the [[Queensland Country Women's Association]] meets at the St Johns Ambulance Rooms at 20 Apollonian Vale.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.qcwa.org.au/branch-locations/|title=Branch Locations|publisher=[[Queensland Country Women's Association]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181226010724/http://www.qcwa.org.au/branch-locations/|access-date=26 December 2018|archive-date=26 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nRoad connection to Gympie is via the [[Bruce Highway]].  Rail connects via [[Queensland Rail|QR's]] [[North Coast railway line, Queensland|North Coast railway line]], which is served by daily [[Queensland Rail City network]] services to [[Brisbane]] and [[Traveltrain]] services for long distances. There are few public buses in Gympie and automobiles are the main mode of transportation.\n\n[[Gympie Airport]] is a small local airport located to the south of the town.  It has general aviation, recreational aviation and gliding communities.\n\n==Governance==\nEight councillors are elected to the [[Gympie Region]] local government area.<ref name=\"rfc\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.gympietimes.com.au/story/2012/05/14/are-they-ready-for-council/ |title=Ready for council? My oath |author=Carly Morrissey |accessdate=20 May 2012 |date=14 May 2012 |work=[[The Gympie Times]] }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Electoral district of Gympie]] in the state legislature was created in 1873 and includes [[Tin Can Bay]], [[Rainbow Beach]], [[Cooran]], [[Pomona, Queensland|Pomona]] and parts of the [[Mary Valley]].<ref name=\"loe\"/> In 1893, [[Andrew Fisher]] was elected to the [[Legislative Assembly of Queensland]] as [[Australian Labor Party (Queensland Branch)|Labor]] member for Gympie and went on to become the fifth [[Prime Minister of Australia]].<ref name=\"loe\"/> Gympie's seat was eliminated in 1950 but restored in 1960.<ref name=\"loe\"/> Since 1960, it has been considered a safe State Liberal-National seat having been won by the Country or National Party every election except for a brief period in the early 2000s.<ref name=\"loe\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.gympietimes.com.au/story/2012/03/03/latest-on-elections-with-the-times/ |title=Latest on elections with The Times |accessdate=21 May 2012 |date=3 March 2012 |work=[[The Gympie Times]]}}</ref> (It was held from 2002 to 2006 by [[Elisa Roberts]], first as a member of the [[One Nation (Australia)|One Nation]] party and then as an independent, before returning to the National Party with the election of [[David Gibson (Australian politician)|David Gibson]].)<ref name=\"loe\"/>\n\nAs of 2015, [[Tony Perrett]] of the [[Liberal National Party of Queensland|Liberal National Party]] in the member for [[Electoral district of Gympie|Gympie]] in the [[Queensland Legislative Assembly]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/qld-election-2015/guide/gymp/|title=Gympie|work=Queensland Election 2015|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|last=Green|first=Antony|authorlink=Antony Green|access-date=14 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706143735/http://www.abc.net.au/news/qld-election-2015/guide/gymp/|archive-date=6 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Traveston Crossing Dam==\n{{main|Traveston Crossing Dam}}\n\nThe Queensland Government had plans to build a dam on the Mary River at [[Traveston Crossing Dam|Traveston Crossing]], about {{convert|16|km|mi}} south of Gympie, arguing that there is sound geology and that the South East Queensland region needed greater water security due to the threat of climate change and population growth.<ref name=\"ppnmww\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.qt.com.au/story/2008/03/26/apn-plan-promises-no-more-water/ |title=Plan promises no more water woes |author=Josephine Gillespie |accessdate=19 December 2010 |date=26 March 2008 |newspaper=[[The Queensland Times]] |publisher=APN News & Media |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100622061706/http://www.qt.com.au/story/2008/03/26/apn-plan-promises-no-more-water/ |archivedate=22 June 2010}}</ref> The project was scrapped in 2010.\n\nThe proposed dam would have flooded about 900 properties{{Citation needed|date=December 2010}}. The affected land owners and other shire residents staged rallies protesting against the proposed dam.  Strong opposition to the dam from the wider and international community based on environmental concerns related to the endangered [[Mary River cod]], [[Mary River turtle]], [[giant barred frog]], [[Pearson's green tree frog|Cascade tree frog]] and [[Coxen's fig parrot]] and the vulnerable [[Queensland lungfish]], [[tusked frog]], [[honey blue-eye]] fish, the [[Richmond birdwing]] butterfly and the [[Illidge's ant blue]] butterfly finally shut down the project.\n\n==Notable people==\n<!-- List in alphabetic order by surname -->{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n*[[John Francis Barnes (politician)|John Francis (Frank) Barnes]] \u2013 politician\n*[[John O'Connell Bligh]] \u2013 Native Police Commandant\n*[[Allan Boase]] \u2013 Australian Army Lieutenant General<ref>{{cite web|last=Dicker|first=George|title=Boase, Allan Joseph (1894\u20131964)|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/boase-allan-joseph-9973/text16783|work=Australian Dictionary of Biography|publisher=Australian National University|accessdate=29 September 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20170930221120/http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/boase-allan-joseph-9973/text16783|archivedate=30 September 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Henry Ernest Boote]] \u2013 writer\n* [[Glen Boss]] \u2013 jockey<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.progroupracing.com.au/horse-racing-articles/jockeys/glen-boss|title=Glen Boss Australian Champion Jockey|website=ProGroup Racing|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130309080835/http://www.progroupracing.com.au/horse-racing-articles/jockeys/glen-boss|archive-date=9 March 2013|url-status=dead|access-date=28 April 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Archie Bradley (boxer)|Archie Bradley]] \u2013 boxer\n* [[Jimmy Downey]] \u2013 football player\n* [[Thomas Dunstan]] \u2013 politician<ref>{{cite web|title=Former Members|publisher=[[Parliament of Queensland]]|year=2015|url=http://www.parliament.qld.gov.au/members/former/bio?id=2320501124|accessdate=15 April 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506173120/http://www.parliament.qld.gov.au/members/former/bio?id=2320501124|archivedate=6 May 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Hugo William Du Rietz]] \u2013 gold miner, architect\n* [[Andrew Fisher]] \u2013 Australian Prime Minister\n* [[William Glasgow (general)|Sir Thomas William Glasgow]] \u2013 Australian Army Major General\n*  [[Kaden Groves]] \u2013 professional cyclist\n* [[Darren Hanlon]] \u2013 musician\n* [[Peter Hanlon]] \u2013 sports writer\n* [[Kenneth Hayne]] \u2013 Supreme Court Justice\n* [[Trevor Housley]] \u2013 Postmaster-General\n* [[Angus Finlay Hutton]] \u2013 naturalist\n* [[Thelma Keane]] \u2013 businesswoman\n*[[James Kidgell]] \u2013 politician\n* [[Tracey Lewis]] \u2013 paralympic swimmer\n* [[George Mackay (Australian politician)|George Mackay]] \u2013 politician\n* [[Barry McTaggart]] \u2013 rugby player\n* [[Mathew Mellor]] \u2013 politician\n* [[James Nash (prospector)|James Nash]] \u2013 prospector\n* [[Francis Isidore Power]] \u2013 politician\n* [[Gregory Charles Rivers]] \u2013 actor\n* [[Marjorie Roche]] \u2013 Red Cross nurse\n* [[Christopher Scott (cyclist)|Christopher Scott]] \u2013 paralympic cyclist<ref>\u2013 cyclist{{cite web|archiveurl=http://pandora.nla.gov.au/nph-arch/2000/Z2000-Jan-20/http://www.ausport.gov.au/olym96/paracycl.html |archivedate=20 January 2000|url=http://www.ausport.gov.au/olym96/paracycl.html|title=Australians at the 1996 Atlanta Paralympics: Cyclists|publisher=[[Australian Sports Commission]]|accessdate=15 January 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Christopher Sheehy|Sir Christopher Sheehy]] \u2013 dairy industry administrator\n* [[Ann Caroline Sherry]] [[Officer of the Order of Australia|AO]] \u2013 businesswoman \n* [[Jacob Stumm]] \u2013 newspaper owner\n* [[Harry Sunderland]] \u2013 rugby administrator<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/sunderland-harry-11803|title = Australian Dictionary of Biography|date = 2002|accessdate = 30 March 2015|website = Sunderland, Harry (1889\u20131964)|publisher = Australian Dictionary of Biography|last = Edmond|first = Scott|url-status = live|archiveurl = http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20150330175254/http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/sunderland-harry-11803|archivedate = 30 March 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Estelle Thompson]] \u2013 crime novelist \n* [[Vivian Tozer]] \u2013 politician\n* [[The Amity Affliction]] \u2013 musicians\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Queensland}}\n* [[The Gympie Times]], a current newspaper\n* [[The Gympie Miner]], a former newspaper\n* [[Gympie Cemetery]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Gympie, Queensland}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091024154244/http://www.cooloola.org.au/Destinations/Gympie/Gympie.aspx Gympie Cooloola Tourism]\n* [http://www.gympie.qld.gov.au/ Gympie Region]\n* {{cite web|title=Gympie|url=http://www.queenslandplaces.com.au/gympie|work=Queensland Places|publisher=Centre for the Government of Queensland, University of Queensland}}\n* [https://www.gympie.qld.gov.au/web/library/library-locations Gympie Library]\n\n[[Category:Towns in Queensland]]\n[[Category:Wide Bay\u2013Burnett]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1867]]\n[[Category:Gympie| ]]\n[[Category:1867 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Gympie Region]]\n[[Category:Localities in Queensland]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2012}}\n{{Infobox Australian place\n| type         = town\n| name         = Gympie\n| state        = qld\n| image        =Gympie Town Hall, 2015.jpg\n| caption      =Gympie Town Hall, 2015 \n| postcode     = 4570\n| coordinates  = {{coord|-26.19|152.6655|type:city_region:AU-QLD|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_label_position = left\n| pop          = 21599\n| pop_year     = 2018\n| pop_footnotes = <ref name=ABSSUA/>\n| poprank      =\n| density      =\n| est          = 1867\n| area         = 69.3\n| area_footnotes =  <ref name=\"ABSSUAProf\">{{cite web|title=2011 Census Community Profiles: Gympie|url=http://www.censusdata.abs.gov.au/census_services/getproduct/census/2011/communityprofile/3007|website=ABS Census|publisher=[[Australian Bureau of Statistics]]|accessdate=15 September 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419161356/http://www.censusdata.abs.gov.au/census_services/getproduct/census/2011/communityprofile/3007|archivedate=19 April 2018}}</ref> (2011 urban)\n| lga          = [[Gympie Region]]\n| stategov     = [[Electoral district of Gympie|Gympie]]\n| fedgov       = [[Division of Wide Bay|Wide Bay]]\n| dist1        = 160\n| location1    = Brisbane\n| mintemp      = 13.6\n| maxtemp      = 27.1\n| rainfall     = 1132.9\n| near-n              = [[Araluen, Queensland|Araluen]]\n| near-ne             = [[Victory Heights, Queensland|Victory Heights]]\n| near-e              = [[Victory Heights, Queensland|Victory Heights]]\n| near-se             = [[Monkland, Queensland|Monkland]]\n| near-s              = [[Monkland, Queensland|Monkland]]\n| near-sw             = [[Southside, Queensland|Southside]]\n| near-w              = [[Widgee Crossing North, Queensland|Widgee Crossing North]]\n| near-nw             = [[Two Mile, Queensland|Two Mile]]\n}}\n\n'''Gympie''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0261|\u026a|m|p|i}}<ref>''[[Macquarie Dictionary|Macquarie Dictionary, Fourth Edition]]'' (2005). Melbourne, The Macquarie Library Pty Ltd. {{ISBN|1-876429-14-3}}</ref> is a town and a [[Suburbs and localities (Australia)|locality]] in the [[Gympie Region]], [[Queensland]], Australia.<ref name=qpnt>{{cite QPN|15149|Gympie|town in Gympie Region|accessdate=6 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=qpnl>{{cite QPN|46339|Gympie|locality in Gympie Region|accessdate=6 November 2017}}</ref> Located in the [[Wide Bay-Burnett]] district, Gympie is about {{convert|160|km|mi|-1}} north of the state capital, [[Brisbane]]. The city lies on the [[Mary River (Queensland)|Mary River]], which floods the town periodically.  Gympie is the administrative centre for the [[Gympie Region]] area. As at June 2018 Gympie had a population of 21,599.<ref name=ABSSUA>{{cite web|title=3218.0 \u2013 Regional Population Growth, Australia, 2017\u201318: Population Estimates by Significant Urban Area, 2008 to 2018|url=http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/DetailsPage/3218.02017-18|website=Australian Bureau of Statistics|publisher=[[Australian Bureau of Statistics]]|date=27 March 2019|accessdate=25 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327110730/http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/DetailsPage/3218.02017-18|archive-date=27 March 2019|url-status=live}} Estimated resident population, 30 June 2018.</ref>\n\nGympie is famous for its gold field.<ref name=\"ewg\">{{cite book |title=Encyclopedia of World Geography |last=Khan |first=M. Ali |author2=A.Balakishan |year=2007 |publisher=Sarup & Sons |isbn=8176257737 |page=45 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s-HoFag2kDcC |accessdate=20 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629121324/https://books.google.com/books?id=s-HoFag2kDcC |archive-date=29 June 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> It contains a number of historic buildings registered on the [[Queensland Heritage Register]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Plan of Leases and Claims on the Deep Lead, Gympie, 1869.jpg|left|thumb|Map of gold mining leases and claims on the Deep Lead, 1869]]\n''[[Gabi-Gabi language|Gubbi Gubbi]] (Kabi Kabi, Cabbee, Carbi, Gabi Gabi)'' is an [[Australian Aboriginal language]] formerly spoken by the indigenous peoples of the [[Sunshine Coast Region]] and [[Gympie Region]], particularly the towns of Caloundra, [[Noosa Heads, Queensland|Noosa Heads]], Gympie and extending north towards [[Maryborough, Queensland|Maryborough]] and south to [[Caboolture, Queensland|Caboolture]]''.<ref>{{Cite SLQ-CC-BY|url=https://maps.slq.qld.gov.au/iyil/view/13|title=Gubbi Gubbi|website=Queensland Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander languages map|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref>''\n\nGympie's name derives from the [[Gabi-Gabi language|Gubbi Gubbi]] word ''gimpi-gimpi'', which means \"stinging tree\"<ref name=\"his1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gympie.qld.gov.au/categoryholder.asp?CategoryID=3 |title=History |publisher=Gympie Regional Council |accessdate=20 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317135422/http://www.gympie.qld.gov.au/categoryholder.asp?CategoryID=3 |archivedate=17 March 2012}}</ref> and refers to ''[[Dendrocnide moroides]]''. The tree has large, round leaves that have similar properties to [[stinging nettles]]. The town was previously named '''Nashville''', after [[James Nash (prospector)|James Nash]], who discovered gold in the area in 1867.<ref>Hon. C. Wallace, [http://www.cabinet.qld.gov.au/MMS/StatementDisplaySingle.aspx?id=56070 Gympie residents have chance to make their mark on the map] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716094658/http://www.cabinet.qld.gov.au/MMS/StatementDisplaySingle.aspx?id=56070 |date=16 July 2011 }}, 14 January 2008. Accessed 18 April 2009.</ref> The name was changed to Gympie in 1868.<ref>{{Cite web| author1=Unidentified | title=Gympie Fire Station in 1955 | publication-date=1955 | publisher=John Oxley Library, State Library of Queensland | url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/36936554 | accessdate=20 April 2018 }}</ref>[[File:Gympie Hospital, 1891.png|thumb|left|Gympie Hospital, 1891]]Graziers were the original European settlers.  Subsequently, James Nash reported the discovery of 'payable' alluvial gold on 16 October 1867.<ref name=\"adbnash\">Stoodley, June. [http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/nash-james-4286/text6935 Nash, James (1834\u20131913)] {{webarchive|url=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20120509030557/http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/nash-james-4286/text6935 |date=9 May 2012 }}. Australian Dictionary of Biography, National Centre of Biography. Australian National University.</ref> At the time of Nash's discovery, Queensland was suffering from a severe economic depression.  Nash probably saved Queensland from bankruptcy. A memorial fountain in Gympie's Park honours Nash's discovery.<ref name=\"adbnash\" /> The Gympie Gold Rush Festival celebrates the event today.  The Gold Rush Festival holds 10 days of cultural events in October.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://goldrush.org.au/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=484&Itemid=124|title=Gold Rush Festival \u2013 Gympie Goldrush|website=goldrush.org.au|accessdate=19 April 2018}}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> [[Gold mining]] still plays a role in the area's fortunes, along with agriculture (dairy predominantly), timber and tourism.  The gold rush's rapid development led to streets that are in an irregular fashion.<ref name=\"heritage\" />[[File:StateLibQld 1 231369 View of Gympie's streets, ca. 1925.jpg|thumb|left|Lower Mary Street, c.1925]]\n\nGympie Creek Post Office opened on 1 December 1867. It was renamed Gympie in 1868.<ref name=\"Post Office\">{{Cite web  | last = Premier Postal History  | title = Post Office List  | publisher = Premier Postal Auctions  | url = https://www.premierpostal.com/cgi-bin/wsProd.sh/Viewpocdwrapper.p?SortBy=QLD&country=  | accessdate = 10 May 2014  | url-status = live  | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140515223132/http://www.premierpostal.com/cgi-bin/wsProd.sh/Viewpocdwrapper.p?SortBy=QLD&country=  | archivedate = 15 May 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThe railway from Maryborough completed in 1881.<ref name=\"heritage\">{{Cite book |title=Heritage Trails of the Great South East |last=[[Environmental Protection Agency (Queensland)|Environmental Protection Agency]] |year=2000 |publisher=State of Queensland |isbn=0-7345-1008-X |pages=90, 148 }}</ref> The [[North Coast railway line, Queensland#First connection|North Coast railway]] linked Gympie to Brisbane in 1891.<ref name=\"heritage\"/> A fire brigade was in operation in 1900. The state declared Gympie a town in 1903.  A powdered milk factory began operations in 1953.\n\n===Flooding===\n[[File:The Gympie flood, June 19 1873 - 31256978480.jpg|left|thumb|1873 Gympie flood]]\nSignificant floods along the Mary River have caused inundations of the town in 1870, 1873, 1893, 1955, 1968, 1974, [[1989 Gympie, Southern Queensland & Eastern New South Wales Floods|1989]], 1992, [[1999 Gympie - Maryborough, Queensland Floods|1999]], [[2010\u20132011 Queensland floods|2011]]<ref name=\"bommajflood\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bom.gov.au/hydro/flood/qld/brochures/mary/mary.shtml#PreviousFlooding |title=Flood Warning System for the Mary River |publisher=Bureau of Meteorology |accessdate=6 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120421120408/http://www.bom.gov.au/hydro/flood/qld/brochures/mary/mary.shtml#PreviousFlooding |archive-date=21 April 2012 |url-status=live}}</ref> and [[2013 Eastern Australia floods#Queensland|2013]]. The first recorded flood in Gympie was in [[1870 Maryborough - Gympie, Queensland Floods|1870]].  Most of the floods occur between December and April and are typically caused by heavy rainfall in the headwaters to the south.<ref name=\"mmq\" />\n\nThe highest flood ever recorded in Gympie occurred on 2 February 1893 when the river peaked at 25.45&nbsp;m.<ref name=\"mmq\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.gympietimes.com.au/story/2010/03/06/mary-mary-quite-contrary/ |title=Mary, Mary quite contrary |author=Jannette Parke |accessdate=6 May 2012 |date=6 March 2010 |newspaper=[[The Gympie Times]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100311054714/http://www.gympietimes.com.au/story/2010/03/06/mary-mary-quite-contrary/ |archivedate=11 March 2010}}</ref> Gympie was declared a natural disaster area during the 1999 floods.<ref name=\"qfc\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.weeklytimesnow.com.au/article/2011/01/10/279851_latest-news.html |title=Qld flood crisis hits Gympie |accessdate=6 May 2012 |date=10 January 2011 |work=weeklytimes.now.com.au |work=The Weekly Times|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120508060206/http://www.weeklytimesnow.com.au/article/2011/01/10/279851_latest-news.html |archivedate=8 May 2012}}</ref> The river peaked at 21.9&nbsp;m then.\n\nNumerous highways and roads in and around the town which were destroyed or damaged during floods in 2011 was repaired under Operation Queenslander,<ref name=\"rfr\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.gympietimes.com.au/story/2012/05/07/road-flood-repairs-on-going/ |title=Road flood repairs on-going |accessdate=20 May 2012 |date=7 May 2012 |work=[[The Gympie Times]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120518064846/http://www.gympietimes.com.au/story/2012/05/07/road-flood-repairs-on-going/ |archivedate=18 May 2012}}</ref> the name given to post-flood reconstruction efforts in Queensland.\n\nIn March 2012, the [[Gympie Regional Council]] decided to spend about $30,000 for a [[cost benefit analysis]] on flood mitigation measures.<ref name=\"staf\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/story/2012/03/09/staying-afloat-we-dont-have-to-drown/ |title=Staying afloat |accessdate=6 May 2012 |date=9 March 2012 |newspaper=Sunshine Coast Daily |publisher=Sunshine Coast Newspaper Company }}</ref>\n\n== Heritage listings ==\n[[File:Gympie Court House.jpg|thumb|Gympie Court House, 2012]]\nGympie has a number of [[heritage-listed]] sites, including:\n* Brisbane Road: [[Monkland State School Residence]]<ref>{{cite QHR|16749|Monkland State School Residence|602013|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 2 Caledonian Hill: [[Gympie Town Hall]]<ref>{{cite QHR|28821|Gympie Town Hall Reserve Complex|602789|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* Channon Street: [[Gympie Court House]]<ref>{{cite QHR|15308|Gympie Court House|600533|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* Channon Street: [[Old Gympie Post Office]]<ref>{{cite QHR|15309|My Country; Old Post Office|600534|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* Channon Street: [[Surface Hill Uniting Church]]<ref>{{cite QHR|16292|Surface Hill Uniting Church|601529|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 26 Channon Street: [[Gympie Lands Office]]<ref>{{cite QHR|20029|Gympie Court House and Lands Office (former)|602778|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* cnr Channon Street and Nash Streets: former [[Queensland National Bank, Gympie|Queensland National Bank]]<ref>{{cite QHR|20026|Queensland National Bank (former)|602773|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* Church Street: [[St Patricks Church, Gympie|St Patricks Church]]<ref>{{cite QHR|16266|St Patricks Church|601503|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 17 Crown Road: former [[Gympie Ambulance Station]]<ref>{{cite QHR|32244|Gympie Ambulance Station (former)|602794|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* Mary Street: [[Gympie and Widgee War Memorial Gates]]<ref>{{cite QHR|15310|Gympie and Widgee War Memorial Gates|600535|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 199 Mary Street: former [[Royal Bank of Queensland, Gympie|Royal Bank of Queensland]]<ref>{{cite QHR|20093|Royal Bank of Queensland (former)|602774|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 216 Mary Street: former [[Crawford and Co Building]]<ref>{{cite QHR|20097|Crawford and Co. Building (former)|602780|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 218 Mary Street: [[Tozer's Building]]<ref>{{cite QHR|20098|Tozer's Building|602779|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 235 Mary Street: [[Smithfield Chambers]]<ref>{{cite QHR|20102|Smithfield Chambers|602777|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 236 Mary Street: former [[Australian Joint Stock Bank, Gympie|Australian Joint Stock Bank]] and former [[Gympie Stock Exchange]] offices & club<ref>{{cite QHR|20103|Australian Joint Stock Bank (former)/Gympie Stock Exchange Offices and Club (former)|602772|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 242 Mary Street: former [[Bank of New South Wales, Gympie|Bank of New South Wales]]<ref>{{cite QHR|20104|Bank of New South Wales (former)|602775|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 39 Nash Street: [[Gympie School of Arts]]<ref>{{cite QHR|16646|Gympie School of Arts|601910|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* River Road: [[Gympie Memorial Park]]<ref>{{cite QHR|31071|Memorial Park|602729|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* 1 Station Road: [[Railway Hotel, Gympie|Railway Hotel]]<ref>{{cite QHR|19662|Railway Hotel|602540|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n* Tozer Street: [[Gympie railway station]]<ref>{{cite QHR|16772|Gympie Railway Station Platform Complex|602036|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Population==\nAccording to the [[2016 Australian census|2016 census]] of Population, there 20,966 people in Gympie.\n* Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people made up 3.9% of the population. \n* 82.4% of people were born in Australia. The next most common countries of birth were England 2.6%, New Zealand 1.9% and Philippines 0.6%.   \n* 89.6% of people spoke only English at home. \n* The most common responses for religion were No Religion 30.1%, Catholic 16.8% and Anglican 15.6%.<ref name=ABSSUACensus16>{{Census 2016 AUS|id=3007|name=Gympie (Significant Urban Area)|accessdate=24 March 2019|quick=on}}[[File:CC-BY icon.svg|50px]] Material was copied from this source, which is available under a [https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/ Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171016050101/https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/ |date=16 October 2017 }}.</ref>\n\n==Climate==\nGympie has a [[humid subtropical climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]]: '''Cfa''').\n\n<br />\n{{Weather box\n|location = Gympie (1870\u20132019)\n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n|Jan record high C = 42.4\n|Feb record high C = 41.3\n|Mar record high C = 38.1\n|Apr record high C = 35.6\n|May record high C = 32.8\n|Jun record high C = 29.2\n|Jul record high C = 30.2\n|Aug record high C = 34.3\n|Sep record high C = 38.2\n|Oct record high C = 40.1\n|Nov record high C = 42.2\n|Dec record high C = 42.0\n|year record high C = 42.4 \n|Jan high C = 31.3\n|Feb high C = 30.4\n|Mar high C = 29.3\n|Apr high C = 27.3\n|May high C = 24.5\n|Jun high C = 22.1\n|Jul high C = 21.9\n|Aug high C = 23.4\n|Sep high C = 26.1\n|Oct high C = 28.3\n|Nov high C = 30.2\n|Dec high C = 31.3\n|year high C = 27.2\n|Jan low C = 19.6\n|Feb low C = 19.7\n|Mar low C = 18.2\n|Apr low C = 14.7\n|May low C = 10.8\n|Jun low C = 8.0 \n|Jul low C = 6.3\n|Aug low C = 7.1\n|Sep low C = 10.3\n|Oct low C = 13.8\n|Nov low C = 16.5\n|Dec low C = 18.6\n|year low C = 13.6\n|Jan record low C = 12.0\n|Feb record low C = 12.3\n|Mar record low C = 9.8\n|Apr record low C = 3.6\n|May record low C = -0.9\n|Jun record low C = -3.3\n|Jul record low C = -4.3\n|Aug record low C = -1.8\n|Sep record low C = 1.3\n|Oct record low C = 4.6\n|Nov record low C = 3.5\n|Dec record low C = 10.1\n|year record low C = -4.3\n|Jan rain mm = 161.9\n|Feb rain mm = 167.3\n|Mar rain mm = 144.7\n|Apr rain mm = 82.9\n|May rain mm = 71.4\n|Jun rain mm = 60.2\n|Jul rain mm = 51.3\n|Aug rain mm = 40.0\n|Sep rain mm = 45.0\n|Oct rain mm = 72.0\n|Nov rain mm = 87.5\n|Dec rain mm = 136.6 \n|Jan rain days = 12.8\n|Feb rain days = 13.6\n|Mar rain days = 14.4\n|Apr rain days = 11.5\n|May rain days = 10.3\n|Jun rain days = 8.3\n|Jul rain days = 6.9\n|Aug rain days = 6.4\n|Sep rain days = 6.7\n|Oct rain days = 8.2\n|Nov rain days = 9.5\n|Dec rain days = 11.2\n|unit rain days = 0.2mm\n|source 1 = [[Bureau of Meteorology (Australia)|Bureau of Meteorology]]<ref>{{BoM Aust stats|site_ref=cw_040093_All|site_name=Gympie|accessdate=23 March 2013|date=March 2013}}</ref>\n|date=June 2015}}\n\n==Attractions==\n[[File:Rattler Hero 1.jpg|alt=|thumb|The Mary Valley Rattler C17 Locomotive 967]]\nThe Gympie Gold Mining and Historical Museum houses memorabilia from the early gold mining era, as well as displays showcasing military, rural, transport, communications, and steam development in Australia.  The WoodWorks Museum provides an insight into the timber industry and social history of yesteryear through displays and demonstrations. Features include a large selection of pioneering hand tools, a 1925 Republic truck, bullock wagons, and a blacksmith shop.\n\nThe [[Mary Valley Rattler|Valley Rattler]] steam train is a tourist train that began operations in 1996. It follows the Mary River through the forests and plantations of the Mary Valley to [[Dagun, Queensland|Dagun]].<ref name=\"qpmv\">{{cite web |url=http://queenslandplaces.com.au/node/4888 |title=Mary Valley |work=Queensland Places |publisher=Centre for the Government of Queensland, University of Queensland. |accessdate=20 May 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025043958/http://queenslandplaces.com.au/node/4888 |archivedate=25 October 2012}}</ref> The train departs and returns to the [[Gympie railway station|Old Gympie Railway Station]] in Tozer Street, an original railway station from the 1900s gold rush.\n\nApproximately 25 km south of Gympie, the town of Amamoor hosts the annual National Country Music Muster. Held over six days and nights in August in the [[Amamoor Forest Reserve]],<ref name=\"asf\">{{cite web |url=http://www.derm.qld.gov.au/parks/amamoor/camping.html |title=Amamoor State Forest and Forest Reserve \u2013 Camping information |publisher=Department of Environment and Resource Management |date=14 October 2011 |accessdate=20 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120509195323/http://www.derm.qld.gov.au/parks/amamoor/camping.html |archivedate=9 May 2012}}</ref> the Muster is the largest outdoor country music festival in Australia.\n\nGympie's Mary St offers a wide array of bars, cafes, and shops with 19th Century Victorian architecture. The historic Railway Hotel was built in 1915 and is listed on the [[Queensland Heritage Register]].<ref name=\"poh\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.gympietimes.com.au/story/2012/01/17/piece-of-history-goes-on-the-block/ |title=Piece of history goes on the block |author=Lee Gailer |accessdate=6 May 2012 |date=17 January 2012 |newspaper=[[The Gympie Times]] |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120202054912/http://www.gympietimes.com.au/story/2012/01/17/piece-of-history-goes-on-the-block/ |archivedate=2 February 2012}}</ref> The Gympie Town Hall Reserve Complex, built in 1890, was added to the Queensland Heritage Register in 2011.<ref name=\"shl\">{{cite web |url=http://www.qldheritage.org.au/state-heritage-listing-for-gympie-icon.html |title=State heritage listing for Gympie icon |date=9 September 2012 |publisher=Queensland Heritage Council |accessdate=21 May 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130329021958/http://www.qldheritage.org.au/state-heritage-listing-for-gympie-icon.html |archivedate=29 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Mothar Mountain Speedway]] is Gympie's local raceway which hosts the motorsport Speedway A.K.A [[dirt track racing]]. Mothar Mountain Speedway is promoted by the Gympie Saloon Car Club Ltd.\n \nThe annual [[Heart of Gold International Short Film Festival]] is held in Gympie in March.[[File:Big Pineapple, Gympie, Queensland.jpg|thumb|[[Australia's big things|Big Pineapple]], Gympie (now removed)|alt=]]\n\n24 km south-east of Gympie, [[Woondum National Park]] provides access to subtropical rainforest, creeks and granite outcrops.<ref name=\"wnp\">{{cite web |url=http://www.derm.qld.gov.au/parks/woondum/index.html |title=Woondum National Park |date=9 June 2011 |publisher=Department of Environment and Resource Management |accessdate=21 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120505053817/http://www.derm.qld.gov.au/parks/woondum/index.html |archivedate=5 May 2012}}</ref> Facilities include picnic tables, barbecues, firewood, fresh water, amenities, and bush-walking tracks. Access is by dirt road and a high-clearance vehicle is recommended.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/story/2010/03/24/trip-mothar-mountain-rock-pools/ |title=Trip to Mothar Mountain rock pools |author=Alexia Purcell |accessdate=21 May 2012 |date=24 March 2010 |newspaper=Sunshine Coast Daily |publisher=Sunshine Coast Newspaper Company }}</ref>\n\nAbout 30 minutes' drive east of Gympie is [[Tin Can Bay]], where one can hand-feed [[Indo-Pacific hump-backed dolphin]]s. The feeding is regulated for the protection of the dolphins.  \n\nGympie and the surrounding area is part of the [[Great Sandy Biosphere Reserve]], listed by [[UNESCO]] as a world conservation site.\n\nThe [[Gympie Pyramid]] is also a minor attraction.\n\n[[Gympie Cemetery]] crawls are run by the Gympie Family History Society.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gympiefhs.egympie.com.au/Cemetery%20Crawls.htm |title=Cemetery Crawls |publisher=Gympie Family History Society Inc. |accessdate=19 March 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160229184008/http://www.gympiefhs.egympie.com.au/Cemetery%20Crawls.htm |archivedate=29 February 2016}}</ref> Participants learn about the town's pioneering families.\n\n==Education==\nGympie has many schools, reflecting its importance as a regional service centre. State primary schools include:\n* Gympie West State School opened on 28 January 1958.<ref name=\"qs\">{{Cite QldSchool|accessdate=18 April 2019}}</ref>\n* Chatsworth State School opened on 18 April 1900.<ref name=qs/>\n* Monkland State School opened on 24 September 1884.<ref name=qs/>\n* Jones Hill State School opened on 29 January 1902.<ref name=qs/>\n* Gympie Central State School opened on 18 October 1869.<ref name=qs/>\n* Two Mile State School opened on 9 July 1883.<ref name=\"qfhs\"/> \n* One Mile State School was the first school opened in Gympie on 20 September 1869 as One Mile Boys State School with the One Mile Girls and Infants State School opening in October 1874. In January 1943, they were merged into One Mile State School.<ref name=\"qfhs\">{{Citation|title=Queensland schools past and present|publication-date=2010|author1=Queensland Family History Society|edition=Version 1.01|publisher=[[Queensland Family History Society]]|isbn=978-1-921171-26-0}}</ref> \n* Gympie East State School opened on 25 January 1965.<ref name=qs/>\n* Gympie South State School opened on 4 July 1910.<ref name=qs/>\n\nState secondary schools include:\n* [[James Nash State High School]] opened on 24 January 1977.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://jamesnashshs.eq.edu.au/Pages/default.aspx|title=James Nash SHS|access-date=29 January 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202060858/https://jamesnashshs.eq.edu.au/Pages/default.aspx|archivedate=2 February 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"qs\"/>\n* [[Gympie State High School]] opened on 29 January 1912.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gympieshs.eq.edu.au/Pages/default.aspx|title=Gympie SHS|access-date=29 January 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204054453/https://gympieshs.eq.edu.au/Pages/default.aspx|archivedate=4 February 2017}}</ref> This school is one of the oldest state secondary schools in Queensland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://education.qld.gov.au/library/edhistory/topics/oldest-sec-schools.html|title=The oldest state secondary schools in Queensland|website=education.qld.gov.au|language=en-AU|access-date=29 January 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180129140634/http://education.qld.gov.au/library/edhistory/topics/oldest-sec-schools.html|archivedate=29 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nPrivate schools offer both primary and secondary education.  They include Victory College, [[Cooloola Christian College]] and [[St Patrick's College, Gympie|St Patrick's]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gympie.qld.gov.au/schools_list.asp|title=Gympie Regional Council \u2013 Schools|accessdate=19 April 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090518203212/http://www.gympie.qld.gov.au/schools_list.asp|archivedate=18 May 2009}}</ref> St Patrick's College in Gympie opened on 30 December 1916.<ref name=qs/>\n\nGympie is home to one campus of the [[Wide Bay Institute of TAFE]] located on Cartwright Road.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.widebay.tafe.qld.gov.au/about_us/campuses/gympie.html |title=Gympie |publisher=Wide Bay Institute of TAFE |accessdate=20 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320173302/http://widebay.tafe.qld.gov.au/about_us/campuses/gympie.html |archivedate=20 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe University of the Sunshine Coast (USC) has a campus in Gympie located on Cartwright Road. This campus offers undergraduate study in primary education, nursing, business, and commerce.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usc.edu.au/learn/the-usc-experience/study-locations/study-in-gympie|title=USC Gympie|website=www.usc.edu.au|accessdate=19 April 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170803235403/http://www.usc.edu.au/learn/the-usc-experience/study-locations/study-in-gympie|archivedate=3 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Amenities ==\nThe [[Gympie Regional Council]] operates a public library at 8\u201314 Mellor Street.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gympie.qld.gov.au/web/library/library-locations|title=Library locations|website=[[Gympie Regional Council]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180131023219/https://www.gympie.qld.gov.au/web/library/library-locations|archive-date=31 January 2018|url-status=live|access-date=31 January 2018}}</ref> It opened in 1995.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.plconnect.slq.qld.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0012/388497/SLQ_StatsBulletin1617_20171109.pdf|title=Public Libraries Statistical Bulletin 2016\u201317|date=November 2017|website=Public Libraries Connect|publisher=[[State Library of Queensland]]|page=13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180130022546/http://www.plconnect.slq.qld.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0012/388497/SLQ_StatsBulletin1617_20171109.pdf|archive-date=30 January 2018|url-status=live|access-date=30 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe Gympie branch of the [[Queensland Country Women's Association]] meets at the St Johns Ambulance Rooms at 20 Apollonian Vale.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.qcwa.org.au/branch-locations/|title=Branch Locations|publisher=[[Queensland Country Women's Association]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181226010724/http://www.qcwa.org.au/branch-locations/|access-date=26 December 2018|archive-date=26 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nRoad connection to Gympie is via the [[Bruce Highway]].  Rail connects via [[Queensland Rail|QR's]] [[North Coast railway line, Queensland|North Coast railway line]], which is served by daily [[Queensland Rail City network]] services to [[Brisbane]] and [[Traveltrain]] services for long distances. There are few public buses in Gympie and automobiles are the main mode of transportation.\n\n[[Gympie Airport]] is a small local airport located to the south of the town.  It has general aviation, recreational aviation and gliding communities.\n\n==Governance==\nEight councillors are elected to the [[Gympie Region]] local government area.<ref name=\"rfc\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.gympietimes.com.au/story/2012/05/14/are-they-ready-for-council/ |title=Ready for council? My oath |author=Carly Morrissey |accessdate=20 May 2012 |date=14 May 2012 |work=[[The Gympie Times]] }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Electoral district of Gympie]] in the state legislature was created in 1873 and includes [[Tin Can Bay]], [[Rainbow Beach]], [[Cooran]], [[Pomona, Queensland|Pomona]] and parts of the [[Mary Valley]].<ref name=\"loe\"/> In 1893, [[Andrew Fisher]] was elected to the [[Legislative Assembly of Queensland]] as [[Australian Labor Party (Queensland Branch)|Labor]] member for Gympie and went on to become the fifth [[Prime Minister of Australia]].<ref name=\"loe\"/> Gympie's seat was eliminated in 1950 but restored in 1960.<ref name=\"loe\"/> Since 1960, it has been considered a safe State Liberal-National seat having been won by the Country or National Party every election except for a brief period in the early 2000s.<ref name=\"loe\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.gympietimes.com.au/story/2012/03/03/latest-on-elections-with-the-times/ |title=Latest on elections with The Times |accessdate=21 May 2012 |date=3 March 2012 |work=[[The Gympie Times]]}}</ref> (It was held from 2002 to 2006 by [[Elisa Roberts]], first as a member of the [[One Nation (Australia)|One Nation]] party and then as an independent, before returning to the National Party with the election of [[David Gibson (Australian politician)|David Gibson]].)<ref name=\"loe\"/>\n\nAs of 2015, [[Tony Perrett]] of the [[Liberal National Party of Queensland|Liberal National Party]] in the member for [[Electoral district of Gympie|Gympie]] in the [[Queensland Legislative Assembly]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/qld-election-2015/guide/gymp/|title=Gympie|work=Queensland Election 2015|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]|last=Green|first=Antony|authorlink=Antony Green|access-date=14 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706143735/http://www.abc.net.au/news/qld-election-2015/guide/gymp/|archive-date=6 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Traveston Crossing Dam==\n{{main|Traveston Crossing Dam}}\n\nThe Queensland Government had plans to build a dam on the Mary River at [[Traveston Crossing Dam|Traveston Crossing]], about {{convert|16|km|mi}} south of Gympie, arguing that there is sound geology and that the South East Queensland region needed greater water security due to the threat of climate change and population growth.<ref name=\"ppnmww\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.qt.com.au/story/2008/03/26/apn-plan-promises-no-more-water/ |title=Plan promises no more water woes |author=Josephine Gillespie |accessdate=19 December 2010 |date=26 March 2008 |newspaper=[[The Queensland Times]] |publisher=APN News & Media |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100622061706/http://www.qt.com.au/story/2008/03/26/apn-plan-promises-no-more-water/ |archivedate=22 June 2010}}</ref> The project was scrapped in 2010.\n\nThe proposed dam would have flooded about 900 properties{{Citation needed|date=December 2010}}. The affected land owners and other shire residents staged rallies protesting against the proposed dam.  Strong opposition to the dam from the wider and international community based on environmental concerns related to the endangered [[Mary River cod]], [[Mary River turtle]], [[giant barred frog]], [[Pearson's green tree frog|Cascade tree frog]] and [[Coxen's fig parrot]] and the vulnerable [[Queensland lungfish]], [[tusked frog]], [[honey blue-eye]] fish, the [[Richmond birdwing]] butterfly and the [[Illidge's ant blue]] butterfly finally shut down the project.\n\n==Notable people==\n<!-- List in alphabetic order by surname -->{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n*[[John Francis Barnes (politician)|John Francis (Frank) Barnes]] \u2013 politician\n*[[John O'Connell Bligh]] \u2013 Native Police Commandant\n*[[Allan Boase]] \u2013 Australian Army Lieutenant General<ref>{{cite web|last=Dicker|first=George|title=Boase, Allan Joseph (1894\u20131964)|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/boase-allan-joseph-9973/text16783|work=Australian Dictionary of Biography|publisher=Australian National University|accessdate=29 September 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20170930221120/http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/boase-allan-joseph-9973/text16783|archivedate=30 September 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Henry Ernest Boote]] \u2013 writer\n* [[Glen Boss]] \u2013 jockey<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.progroupracing.com.au/horse-racing-articles/jockeys/glen-boss|title=Glen Boss Australian Champion Jockey|website=ProGroup Racing|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130309080835/http://www.progroupracing.com.au/horse-racing-articles/jockeys/glen-boss|archive-date=9 March 2013|url-status=dead|access-date=28 April 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Archie Bradley (boxer)|Archie Bradley]] \u2013 boxer\n* [[Jimmy Downey]] \u2013 football player\n* [[Thomas Dunstan]] \u2013 politician<ref>{{cite web|title=Former Members|publisher=[[Parliament of Queensland]]|year=2015|url=http://www.parliament.qld.gov.au/members/former/bio?id=2320501124|accessdate=15 April 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506173120/http://www.parliament.qld.gov.au/members/former/bio?id=2320501124|archivedate=6 May 2016}}</ref>\n* [[Hugo William Du Rietz]] \u2013 gold miner, architect\n* [[Andrew Fisher]] \u2013 Australian Prime Minister\n* [[William Glasgow (general)|Sir Thomas William Glasgow]] \u2013 Australian Army Major General\n*  [[Kaden Groves]] \u2013 professional cyclist\n* [[Darren Hanlon]] \u2013 musician\n* [[Peter Hanlon]] \u2013 sports writer\n* [[Kenneth Hayne]] \u2013 Supreme Court Justice\n* [[Trevor Housley]] \u2013 Postmaster-General\n* [[Angus Finlay Hutton]] \u2013 naturalist\n* [[Thelma Keane]] \u2013 businesswoman\n*[[James Kidgell]] \u2013 politician\n* [[Tracey Lewis]] \u2013 paralympic swimmer\n* [[George Mackay (Australian politician)|George Mackay]] \u2013 politician\n* [[Barry McTaggart]] \u2013 rugby player\n* [[Mathew Mellor]] \u2013 politician\n* [[James Nash (prospector)|James Nash]] \u2013 prospector\n* [[Francis Isidore Power]] \u2013 politician\n* [[Gregory Charles Rivers]] \u2013 actor\n* [[Marjorie Roche]] \u2013 Red Cross nurse\n* [[Christopher Scott (cyclist)|Christopher Scott]] \u2013 paralympic cyclist<ref>\u2013 cyclist{{cite web|archiveurl=http://pandora.nla.gov.au/nph-arch/2000/Z2000-Jan-20/http://www.ausport.gov.au/olym96/paracycl.html |archivedate=20 January 2000|url=http://www.ausport.gov.au/olym96/paracycl.html|title=Australians at the 1996 Atlanta Paralympics: Cyclists|publisher=[[Australian Sports Commission]]|accessdate=15 January 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Christopher Sheehy|Sir Christopher Sheehy]] \u2013 dairy industry administrator\n* [[Ann Caroline Sherry]] [[Officer of the Order of Australia|AO]] \u2013 businesswoman \n* [[Jacob Stumm]] \u2013 newspaper owner\n* [[Harry Sunderland]] \u2013 rugby administrator<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/sunderland-harry-11803|title = Australian Dictionary of Biography|date = 2002|accessdate = 30 March 2015|website = Sunderland, Harry (1889\u20131964)|publisher = Australian Dictionary of Biography|last = Edmond|first = Scott|url-status = live|archiveurl = http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20150330175254/http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/sunderland-harry-11803|archivedate = 30 March 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Estelle Thompson]] \u2013 crime novelist \n* [[Vivian Tozer]] \u2013 politician\n* [[The Amity Affliction]] \u2013 musicians\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Queensland}}\n* [[The Gympie Times]], a current newspaper\n* [[The Gympie Miner]], a former newspaper\n* [[Gympie Cemetery]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Gympie, Queensland}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091024154244/http://www.cooloola.org.au/Destinations/Gympie/Gympie.aspx Gympie Cooloola Tourism]\n* [http://www.gympie.qld.gov.au/ Gympie Region]\n* {{cite web|title=Gympie|url=http://www.queenslandplaces.com.au/gympie|work=Queensland Places|publisher=Centre for the Government of Queensland, University of Queensland}}\n* [https://www.gympie.qld.gov.au/web/library/library-locations Gympie Library]\n\n[[Category:Towns in Queensland]]\n[[Category:Wide Bay\u2013Burnett]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1867]]\n[[Category:Gympie| ]]\n[[Category:1867 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Gympie Region]]\n[[Category:Localities in Queensland]]\n", "name_user": "Davemck", "label": "safe", "comment": "rmv duplicate parm", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gympie"}
{"title_page": "Greater St. Louis", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date = October 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = October 2019}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| official_name                   = Greater St. Louis Metropolitan Area\n| other_name                      = <small>St. Louis, MO-IL</small>\n| settlement_type                 = [[Metropolitan area]]\n| motto                           = Gateway To The West\n| image_skyline                   = GreaterSTLNASA.JPG\n| imagesize                       = 300px\n| image_caption                   = A [[NASA]] image of the Greater St. Louis area\n| image_map                       = St. Louis MSA.svg\n| mapsize                         = 200px\n| map_caption                     = Location in Missouri\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{Flag|United States}}\n| subdivision_type1               = State(s)\n| subdivision_name1               = {{Flag|Missouri}}<br />{{Flag|Illinois}}\n| subdivision_type2               = Largest&nbsp;city\n| subdivision_name2               = {{Flag|St. Louis}}\n| subdivision_type3               = Counties\n| subdivision_name3               = {{Collapsible list\n|title       = List\n|title_style =\n|list_style  =\n|1           = <small>In MSA:</small>\n|2           =  [[St. Louis County, Missouri|St. Louis County]]\n|3           =  [[St. Louis]]\n|4= [[St. Charles County, Missouri|St. Charles]]\n|5= [[Jefferson County, Missouri|Jefferson]]\n|6=[[Franklin County, Missouri|Franklin]]\n|7=[[Lincoln County, Missouri|Lincoln]]\n|8=[[Warren County, Missouri|Warren]]\n|9= [[Madison County, Illinois|Madison]]\n|10=[[St. Clair County, Illinois|St. Clair]]\n|11=[[Monroe County, Illinois|Monroe]]\n|12=[[Clinton County, Illinois|Clinton]]\n|13= [[Jersey County, Illinois|Jersey]]\n|14=[[Bond County, Illinois|Bond]]\n|15=[[Macoupin County, Illinois|Macoupin]]\n|16=[[Calhoun County, Illinois|Calhoun]]\n}}\n| unit_pref                       = US\n| area_total_sq_mi                = 8458\n| area_land_sq_mi                 = 8261 <!-- use for density -->\n| area_water_sq_mi                = 197\n| area_water_percent              = 2.3\n| population_as_of                = 2017\n| population_footnotes            = <ref>{{cite web |url=https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?src=CF |accessdate=2018-12-02 |df= |title=American FactFinder - Results |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721034521/http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=DEC_10_PL_GCTPL2.ST13&prodType=table |archive-date=July 21, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| population_note                 = MSA/CSA = 2017\n| population_total                = \n| population_density_km2          = \n| population_density_sq_mi        = \n| population_metro                = \n| population_density_metro_km2    = \n| population_density_metro_sq_mi  = 339.8 <!-- use 2017 current MSA figure of 2,807,338 / 8261 sq mi. [above] -->\n| population_urban                = \n| population_density_urban_km2    = \n| population_density_urban_sq_mi  = \n| population_blank1_title         = [[Metropolitan Statistical Area|MSA]]\n| population_blank1               = 2,807,338 ([[List of United States metropolitan areas|21st]])\n| population_blank2_title         = [[Combined Statistical Area|CSA]]\n| population_blank2               = 2,911,945 ([[List of core-based statistical areas|19th]])\n| population_density_blank1_km2   = \n| population_density_blank1_sq_mi = \n| timezone                        = [[Central Time Zone|CST]]\n| utc_offset                      = \u22126\n| timezone_DST                    = [[Central Time Zone|CDT]]\n| utc_offset_DST                  = \u22125\n| elevation_footnotes             = <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n| elevation_m                     = 142\u2013390\n| elevation_ft                    = 466\u20131,280\n| area_code                       = 314, 636, 628, 574, 213\n| name                            = \n}}\n\n'''Greater St. Louis''' is a bi-state [[metropolitan area]] that completely surrounds and includes the [[Independent city (United States)|independent city]] of [[St. Louis]], the [[principal city]]. It includes parts of both the U.S. states of [[Missouri]] and [[Illinois]]. The city core is on the Mississippi Riverfront on the border with [[Illinois]] in the geographic center of the metro area. The [[Mississippi River]] bisects the metro area geographically between Illinois and Missouri; however, the Missouri half is much more populous. St. Louis is the largest metro area in Missouri and the second largest in Illinois. [[St. Louis County, Missouri|St. Louis County]] is independent of the City of St. Louis and their two populations are generally tabulated separately.\n\nThe '''St. Louis, MO-IL [[metropolitan statistical area]]''' (MSA)\u2014and the focus of this page\u2014includes the City of St. Louis; the [[Illinois counties]] of [[Bond County, Illinois|Bond]], [[Calhoun County, Illinois|Calhoun]], [[Clinton County, Illinois|Clinton]], [[Jersey County, Illinois|Jersey]], [[Macoupin County, Illinois|Macoupin]], [[Madison County, Illinois|Madison]], [[Monroe County, Illinois|Monroe]], and [[St. Clair County, Illinois|St. Clair]] (known collectively as the '''[[Metro East]]'''); and the [[List of Missouri counties|Missouri counties]] of [[Franklin County, Missouri|Franklin]], [[Jefferson County, Missouri|Jefferson]], [[Lincoln County, Missouri|Lincoln]], [[St. Charles County, Missouri|St. Charles]], [[St. Louis County, Missouri|St. Louis County]] (separate from and not inclusive of the city of St. Louis), and [[Warren County, Missouri|Warren]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/demo/metro-micro/delineation-files.html|title=Delineation Files|last=Bureau|first=US Census|website=www.census.gov|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/maps/metroarea/stcbsa_pg/Feb2013/cbsa2013_MO.pdf|title=Missouri Statistical Areas and Counties|last=|first=|date=December 2, 2018|website=US Census Bureau|access-date=December 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe larger '''St. Louis\u2013St. Charles\u2013Farmington, MO\u2013IL [[combined statistical area]]''' (CSA) includes all of the aforementioned MSA, plus the [[Farmington, Missouri|Farmington, MO micropolitan statistical area]], which includes [[St. Francois County]], [[Missouri]], and the [[Centralia, IL Micropolitan Statistical Area|Centralia, IL micropolitan statistical area]], which includes [[Marion County, Illinois|Marion County]], [[Illinois]].\n\nAs of 2017 data, the MSA is the [[Table of United States Metropolitan Statistical Areas|21st-largest]] in the country that year with a population of 2,807,338;<ref name=\"Bureau\">{{Cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?src=CF|title=American FactFinder - Results|last=Bureau|first=U.S. Census|website=factfinder.census.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-12-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721034521/http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=DEC_10_PL_GCTPL2.ST13&prodType=table|archive-date=July 21, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> however, the CSA is the [[Table of United States Combined Statistical Areas|19th-largest]] in the United States, with a population of 2,911,945.<ref name=\"Bureau\"/> Due to nearly zero growth in St. Louis paired with rapid growth in the Sun Belt and Florida, the St. Louis MSA fell out of the top 20 largest MSAs in the United States in 2017 for the first time since 1840.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/st-louis-region-falls-out-of-the-top-metros-in/article_e4d936f9-6f77-529e-b341-b054b0a01509.html|title=St. Louis region falls out of the Top 20 metros in the U.S.|last=O'Dea|first=Doug Moore, Janelle|work=stltoday.com|access-date=2018-12-02|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.peakbagger.com/pbgeog/histmetropop.aspx|title=Historical Metropolitan Populations of the United States - Peakbagger.com|website=www.peakbagger.com|access-date=2018-12-02}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2018, Greater St. Louis is home to the headquarters of ten of Missouri's eleven [[Fortune 500]] companies,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/fortune500/list/|title=Fortune 500 Companies 2018: Who Made the List|website=Fortune|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-02}}</ref> six [[Fortune 1000|Fortune 1,000]] companies, and two of the top 30 largest private companies in America, as ranked by Forbes.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/largest-private-companies/list/#tab:rank|title=America's Largest Private Companies|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-12-02|language=en}}</ref> The metropolitan area received the [[All-America City Award]] in 2008.\n\n==History==\n{{See also|History of St. Louis}}\n{{expand section|date=August 2018}}\nThe [[history of St. Louis]], Missouri began with the settlement of the St. Louis area by [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] [[Mound builder (people)|mound builders]] who lived as part of the [[Mississippian culture]] from the 9th century to the 15th century, followed by other migrating tribal groups. Starting in the late 17th century, French explorers arrived. Spain took over in 1763 and a trading company established the settlement of St. Louis in February 1764. The city became part of the U.S. through the [[Louisiana Purchase]] in 1803. The [[origins of the American Civil War|American Civil War]] saw St. Louis had a small skirmish on its outskirts, but was held under [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] control. After the war, the city expanded its railroad connections and industrial activity.\n\n==Counties and municipalities in Greater St. Louis==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto;\"\n|+Population of counties in Greater St. Louis (July 2018 estimate) <ref name=\"regional\">{{cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/community_facts.xhtml|title=2018 Population Estimates|last=|first=|date=|website=US Census Bureau|publisher=US Census Bureau|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170108154236/https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml|archive-date=January 8, 2017|accessdate=December 16, 2019|df=}}</ref>\n! State !! County !! Population\n|-\n| Illinois || [[Bond County, Illinois|Bond]]|| 16,630\n|-\n| Illinois || [[Calhoun County, Illinois|Calhoun]]|| 4,802\n|-\n| Illinois || [[Clinton County, Illinois|Clinton]]|| 37,639\n|-\n| Illinois || [[Jersey County, Illinois|Jersey]]|| 21,847\n|-\n| Illinois || [[Macoupin County, Illinois|Macoupin]]|| 45,313\n|-\n| Illinois || [[Madison County, Illinois|Madison]]|| 264,461\n|-\n| Illinois || [[Monroe County, Illinois|Monroe]]|| 34,335\n|-\n| Illinois || [[St. Clair County, Illinois|St. Clair]]|| 261,059\n|-\n| Missouri || [[Franklin County, Missouri|Franklin]]|| 103,670\n|-\n| Missouri || [[Jefferson County, Missouri|Jefferson]]|| 224,347\n|-\n| Missouri || [[Lincoln County, Missouri|Lincoln]]|| 57,686\n|-\n| Missouri || [[St. Charles County, Missouri|St. Charles]]|| 399,182\n|-\n| Missouri || [[St. Louis|St. Louis City]]|| 302,838\n|-\n| Missouri || [[St. Louis County, Missouri|St. Louis]]|| 996,945\n|-\n| Missouri || [[Warren County, Missouri|Warren]]|| 34,711\n|-\n|}\n{{US Census population\n|1830= 57548\n|1840= 126038\n|1850= 237149\n|1860= 410104\n|1870= 645306\n|1880= 712690\n|1890= 833029\n|1900= 1025280\n|1910= 1250094\n|1920= 1380740\n|1930= 1592874\n|1940= 1674411\n|1950= 1928159\n|1960= 2284794\n|1970= 2557457\n|1980= 2497882\n|1990= 2609421\n|2000= 2730984\n|2010= 2853060\n|estyear=2015\n|estimate= 2878108\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2015\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/popest/data/counties/totals/2015/CO-EST2015-alldata.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20160708144914/