inted-cbfc-member/ |title=Sanskar Bharti activist appointed CBFC member }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-rss-now-wants-street-plays-that-will-teach-indian-culture-2262760 |title=RSS now wants street plays that will teach Indian culture |date=10 October 2016 }}</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bibliography of the Sangh Parivar]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n* {{citation |first1=Walter K. |last1=Andersen |authorlink=Walter K. Andersen |first2=Shridhar D. |last2=Damle |title=The Brotherhood in Saffron: The Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh and Hindu Revivalism |origyear=Originally published by Westview Press |publisher=Vistaar Publications |location=Delhi |year=1987 |ref=harv}}\n* {{citation |author=Carol A. Breckenridge, Sheldon Pollock, [[Homi K. Bhabha]], Dipesh Chakrabarty |title=Cosmopolitanism |publisher=[[Duke University Press]] |location=Durham, NC |year=2002 |isbn=978-0-8223-2899-5 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/cosmopolitanism0000unse }}\n* {{citation |last=Bhatt |first=Chetan |title=Hindu Nationalism |year=2001 |publisher=Berg Publishers |location=Oxford, UK / New York, NY |isbn=978-1-85973-348-6 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/hindunationalism00chet }}\n* {{citation |last=Chitkara |first=M. G. |ref=harv |title=Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh: National Upsurge |publisher=APH Publishing |year=2004 |isbn=9788176484657}}\n* {{citation |last1=de la Cadena |first1=Marisol |first2=Orin |last2=Starn |title=Indigenous Experience Today |year=2007 |publisher=Berg Publishers |location=Oxford, UK |isbn=978-1-84520-518-8}}\n* {{citation |last=Fuller |first=Christopher |title=The Camphor Flame |year=2004 |publisher=Princeton University Press |location=Princeton, NJ |isbn=978-0-691-12048-5}}\n* {{citation |last=Jaffrelot |first=Christophe |authorlink=Christophe Jaffrelot |title=The Hindu Nationalist Movement and Indian Politics |publisher=C. Hurst & Co. Publishers |year=1996 |isbn=978-1850653011 |ref=harv}}\n* {{citation |last=Jaffrelot |first=Christophe |authorlink=Christophe Jaffrelot |title=Hindu Nationalism |year=2007 |publisher=Princeton University Press |location=Princeton, NJ / Woodstock, UK |isbn=978-0-691-13098-9}}\n* {{citation |last=Jaffrelot |first=Christophe |authorlink=Christophe Jaffrelot |title=Religion, Caste, and Politics in India |year=2011 |publisher=C Hurst & Co |isbn=978-1849041386}}\n* {{citation |last=Jelen |first=Ted Gerard |title=Religion and Politics in Comparative Perspective: The One, The Few, and The Many |year=2002 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=Cambridge, UK |isbn=978-0-521-65031-1 |ref=harv}}\n* {{citation |last=Mishra |first=Pankaj |authorlink=Pankaj Mishra |title=Temptations of the West: How to be Modern in India, Pakistan, Tibet and Beyond |year=2006 |publisher=Macmillan |location=New York City |isbn=978-0-374-17321-0}}\n* {{citation |last=Saha |first=Santosh |title=Religious Fundamentalism in the Contemporary World: Critical Social and Political Issues |year=2004 |publisher=Lexington Press |location=Lexington, MA |isbn=978-0-7391-0760-7}}\n* {{citation |last=Sarkar |first=Sumit |title=The Fascism of the Sangh Parivar |year=1993 |publisher=Economic and Political Weekly}}\n* {{citation |last=Thakurta |first=Paranjoy Guha |author2=Shankar Raghuraman |title=A Time of Coalitions: Divided We Stand |year=2004 |publisher=SAGE |location=New Delhi, India/Thousand Oaks, CA/London, UK |isbn=978-0-7619-3237-6 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ur6GAwAAQBAJ}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{Sangh Parivar}}\n{{Bharatiya Janata Party |state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Sangh Parivar| ]]\n[[Category:Bharatiya Janata Party]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Advert|date=July 2019}}\n{{POV|date=July 2019}}\n{{POV check|talk=NPOV dispute|date=December 2018}} \n}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2020}}  \n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}} \nThe '''Sangh Parivar''' ([[translation]]: \"Family of the [[Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh]]\" or the \"RSS family\"{{sfn|Jaffrelot|1996 |loc=[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=iVsfVOTUnYEC&pg=PA123 p.&nbsp;123]}}{{sfn|Andersen|Damle|1987|p=115}}<ref>{{citation |first=Thomas Blom |last=Hansen |chapter=Controlled Emancipation: Women and Hindu Nationalism |editor1=Bodil Folke Frederiksen |editor2=Fiona Wilson |title=Ethnicity, Gender and the Subversion of Nationalism |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UwvKAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA93 |year=2014 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-135-20566-9 |page=93}}: \"The RSS usually calls its network of organisation the RSS family (Sangh Parivar), consciously evoking connotations of warmth, security and emotional attachment beyond ideology and reasoning. The family metaphor is central and highly operational as an instrument of recruitment and cohesion for the movement, which offers a sort of surrogate family to the activists. The family metaphor also refers to the authoritarian and paternalist authority structure which operates within the movement.\"</ref>) refers, as an [[umbrella term]], to the collection of [[Hindu nationalist]] organisations spawned by the [[Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh]] (RSS) and remain affiliated to it.  These include the political party [[Bharatiya Janata Party]], religious organisation [[Vishva Hindu Parishad]], students union [[Akhil Bharatiya Vidyarthi Parishad]], religious militant group [[Bajrang Dal]] and the worker's union [[Bharatiya Kisan Sangh|Bharatiya Kishan Sangh]]. It is also often taken to include allied organisations such as the [[Shiv Sena]], which share the ideology of the RSS. The Sangh Parivar represents the Hindu nationalist movement of India.<ref name=\"saha\">{{harvnb|Saha|2004|p=274}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn the 1960s, the volunteers of the RSS joined the different social and political movements in India, including the [[Bhoodan]], a land reform movement led by prominent [[Gandhian]] [[Vinobha Bhave]]<ref>Suresh Ramabhai, Vinoba and his mission, Published by Akhil Bharat Sarv Seva Sangh, 1954</ref> and the [[Sarvodaya]] led by another Gandhian [[Jayaprakash Narayan]].<ref name=\"martha\">Martha Craven Nussbaum, The Clash Within: Democracy, Religious Violence, and India's Future, Published by Harvard University Press, 2007 {{ISBN|0-674-02482-6}}, {{ISBN|978-0-674-02482-3}}</ref> RSS also supported the formation of a trade union, the [[Bharatiya Mazdoor Sangh]] and a student's organisation [[Akhila Bharatiya Vidyarthi Parishad]] and many other organisations like [[Seva Bharati]], Lok Bharati, Deendayal Research Institute etc.\n\nThese organisations started and supported by the RSS volunteers came to be known collectively as the Sangh Parivar.<ref name=\"smith\">Smith, David James, Hinduism and Modernity P189, Blackwell Publishing {{ISBN|0-631-20862-3}}</ref> Next few decades have seen a steady growth in the influence of the Sangh Parivar in the social and political space of India.\n\n==Philosophy==\n===Culture and diversity===\nSangh ideology [[M. S. Golwalkar]] articulated the Sangh's vision on diversity and pluralism, as follows, \"Individuals and nations in all parts of the globe have distinctive traits and features, each of them having its own place in the scheme of the universe. The different human groups are marching forward, all towards the same goal, each in its own way and in keeping with its own characteristic genius. The destruction of the special characteristics, whether of an individual, or of a group, will therefore not only destroy the natural beauty of harmony but also its joy of self-expression. Evolution of human life also, which is a multi-faced one, is retarded thereby\".<ref>M S Golwalkar, Bunch of Thoughts, Publishers: Sahitya Sindhu Prakashana</ref>\n\nThe political opponents of the Sangh Parivar have often termed Sangh Parivar's concerns about cultural intrusion by the Western commercial interests as 'Rightist'.<ref name=\"Thakurta & Raghuraman, 2004:91\">{{harvnb|Thakurta|Raghuraman|2004|loc=[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ur6GAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA91 p.&nbsp;91]}}</ref> [[David Frawley]] argues that the cause is similar to that of native and tribal people all over the world, like Native American and African groups trying to protect their native cultures.<ref name=\"David Frawley 2001\">Hinduism and the Clash of Civilizations/David Frawley. New Delhi, Voice of India, 2001, xiv, 247 p., {{ISBN|81-85990-72-7}}.</ref>\n\n===Economics===\nWhile the [[BJP]] governments have been progressively seen to be industry friendly,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hindu.com/2008/07/20/stories/2008072053910400.htm |title=New Delhi News : BJP assures industrialists of good deal |work=The Hindu|date=20 July 2008 |accessdate=4 September 2010 |location=Chennai, India}}</ref> the opinions and the views of the Sangh Parivar constituents like Bharatiya Mazdoor Sangh (BMS) find consonance with the known leftist stands on labour rights.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Economics: A Bharatiya View Point |date=2002 |url=http://www.bms.org.in/htm/economics.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030221084505/http://bms.org.in/htm/economics.htm |archivedate=21 February 2003 |url-status=dead}}</ref> The Sangh Parivar, as a whole, even the BJP in its earlier days, has advocated 'Swadeshi' (Self Reliance). Sangh Parivar leaders have been very vocal in their criticism of globalization especially its impact on the poor and native people. They have been suspicious of the role of international agencies such as the [[World Bank]] and the [[International Monetary Fund]].<ref>{{Cite news |author=Gupta, Sharad |title=BJP gears up to take on 'ideological ally' |work=The Indian Express|date=14 November 2000 |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/ie/daily/20001124/ina24069.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030123000202/http://www.indianexpress.com/ie/daily/20001124/ina24069.html |archivedate=23 January 2003 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Sangh constituents have advocated and promoted decentralized village centric economic growth with emphasis on ecological protection.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.organiser.org/dynamic/modules.php?name=Content&pa=showpage&pid=269&page=12 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20081230132925/http://www.organiser.org/dynamic/modules.php?name=Content&pa=showpage&pid=269&page=12 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2008-12-30 |title=Content |publisher=Organiser |accessdate=4 September 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Ecology===\nThe constituents of the Sangh Parivar have been known for their demands for steps to \"protect the environment, natural-ecology and agro-economy\" and for establishment of a \"self-reliant village-oriented economy\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sacw.net/DC/CommunalismCollection/ArticlesArchive/GeetaPuriAug08.html |title=Hindutva and Politics: The case of Vishwa Hindu Parishad |publisher=Sacw.net |accessdate=4 September 2010}}</ref> They have been vocal in their demand against the use of Chemical fertilizers and have supported preservation and development of [[Organic farming]] in India.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sanghparivar.org/blog/rkm/unique-sangh-experiment-in-rural-development-by-pramod-kumar-in-mohad |title=Sangh Parivar |website=www.sanghparivar.org}}</ref> Many of these views are seen to mirror the concerns of the [[Green party]].<ref name=\"David Frawley 2001\" />\n\nThe [[Bharatiya Janata Party]], a constituent of Sangh Parivar included the concerns on [[global warming]] in its election manifesto for the National Elections of 2009.<ref name=\"climate\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/holnus/002200904031568.htm |title=BJP promises measures to combat climate change }}</ref> The manifesto promised prioritising \"Combating climate change and global warming\",  \"programmes to arrest the melting of Himalayan glaciers\", \"afforestation\" and emphasis on \"protecting India's biodiversity\".<ref name=climate /><ref>{{citation |title=Congress Voted to Power Why? |author=Yasir Hussain |publisher=Readworthy |year=2008 |page=213 |quote=BJP will pursue national growth objectives through an ecologically sustainable pathway}}</ref>\n\n===Reception===\nThe Sangh Parivar has been described with monikers spanning the spectrum from \"patriotic Hindus\"<ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/articleshow/761560.cms VHP mail: BJP is like 'secular' Cong] [[Times of India]] \u2013 1 July 2004</ref> and \"[[Hindu nationalist]]\".<ref name=\"saha\" /> Some have also labeled them \"Hindu chauvinist\".<ref>Breckenridge, Pollock, Bhabha, Chakravarty 2002:56</ref> While its constituent organisations present themselves as embedded in the traditional ethos of Hinduism, their ideological opponents have characterized them as the representatives of authoritarian, [[xenophobia|xenophobic]] and majoritarian religious nationalism in India,<ref name=\"Bhatt4\">{{harvnb|Bhatt|2002|p=4}}</ref> furthermore these organization have been also documented for alleged acts of ''[[Saffron terror]]''.<ref>[http://www.frontline.in/static/html/fl2822/stories/20111104282207800.htm] [[Frontline (magazine)|Frontline]] \u2013 22 Oct. - Nov. 04, 2011</ref> Flemish Indologist [[Koenraad Elst]] has challenged the critics, in his 2001 book ''[[The Saffron Swastika]]'', he wrote \"So far, the polemical arrows have all been shot from one side, replies from the other side being extremely rare or never more than piecemeal.\"<ref>{{citation |title=The Saffron Swastika |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9G3XAAAAMAAJ |page=9 |first=Koenraad |last=Elst |publisher=Voice of India |year=2001 |isbn=978-81-85990-69-9}}</ref>\n\n==Social impact==\nThe activities of the Sangh Parivar have had considerable social and religious impact.<ref>Human Development and Social Power: Perspectives from South Asia, By Ananya Mukherjee Reed, Routledge, page 71</ref> And considerable influence over country's educational, social and defense policies.<ref>p. 8, Human Rights Watch, By F\u00e9d\u00e9ration internationale des droits de l'homme</ref>\n\n===Social reform===\nIn 1979, the religious wing of the Sangh Parivar, the [[Vishwa Hindu Parishad]] got the Hindu saints and religious leaders to reaffirm that untouchability and caste discrimination had no religious sanction in the Hindu scriptures and texts.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vhp.org/whc2.php |title=VHP website |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090530203527/http://www.vhp.org/whc2.php |archivedate=30 May 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref> The Vishwa Hindu Parishad is also spearheading efforts to ordain Dalits as priests in temples across India, positions that were earlier usually occupied only by people of \"upper castes\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/news/1999/feb/19kerala.htm |title=Rediff on the NeT: VHP has dalit ordained as priest in Kerala |publisher=Rediff.com |date=19 February 1999 |accessdate=4 September 2010}}</ref> In 1983, RSS founded a dalit organization called [[Samajik Samrasta Manch]].<ref name=\"Basu\">{{citation |title=Violent Conjunctures in Democratic India |page=190 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TTrjCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA190&dq=sangh+parivar#v=onepage&q=sangh%20parivar&f=false |first=Amrita |last=Basu |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=2015 |isbn=9781107089631}}</ref>\n\nThe leaders of the Sangh Parivar have also been involved in the campaigns against female fetocide and movements for the education.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.organiser.org/dynamic/modules.php?name=Content&pa=showpage&page=24&pid=46 |title=Content |publisher=Organiser |accessdate=4 September 2010}}</ref> VHP founded a number of educational institutes such as ''Bharat Sevashram'', ''Hindu Milan Mandir'', ''Ekal Vidalayas'' and schools in tribal locations.<ref name=\"Basu\" />\n\n===Social and political empowerment===\nThe service programs, over the years, have led to the empowerment of the economically and socially underprivileged sections of the society, mostly the tribal, who have long remained politically under-represented. [[Babulal Marandi]] belonging to the tribal community, who was the organizing secretary of [[Vishwa Hindu Parishad]], became the first Chief Minister of the state of [[Jharkhand]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/news/2000/nov/14babu.htm |title=Special: Profile of Babu Lal Marandi |publisher=Rediff.com |date=14 November 2000 |accessdate=4 September 2010}}</ref> Other such leaders of Sangh Parivar who belong to the tribal community include [[Karia Munda]], [[Jual Oram]]; both ministers in the Union Government led by [[Atal Bihari Vajpayee]].\n\nThe emergence of the Sangh Parivar in Indian politics also brought many [[Dalits]] and representatives of the [[Other Backward Class|backward classes]], who had been victims of social neglect, to prominent positions in the Government and Administration.<ref>{{citation |title=Buffalo Nationalism: A Critique of Spiritual Fascism |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=obg96BoDD4QC&pg=PA14&dq |first=Kancha |last=Ilaiah |year=2004 |isbn=9788185604695 |page=14}}</ref> Dr Suraj Bhan, a [[dalit]], who had been a member of the RSS, became the Governor of Uttar Pradesh, the most populous state in India, in 1998.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://indiatodaygroup.com/itoday/20000403/states.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=24 January 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20070701213158/http://indiatodaygroup.com/itoday/20000403/states.html |archivedate=1 July 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Other leaders of the Sangh Parivar from the backward classes, who rose to prominence include [[Kalyan Singh]], the former Chief Minister of UP, [[Uma Bharti]], the former Chief Minister of MP, [[Narendra Modi]], the incumbent Prime Minister of India, [[Gopinath Munde]], the former Deputy Chief Minister of Maharashtra,<ref>{{cite news |author=Prakash Joshi, TNN, 22 Sep 2008, 05.05am IST |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/Mumbai/Cong-NCP_casts_OBC_net_to_woo_Marathas_in_state_/articleshow/3511116.cms |title=Cong-NCP casts OBC net to woo Marathas in state \u2013 Mumbai \u2013 City \u2013 The Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=22 September 2008 |accessdate=4 September 2010}}</ref> and [[Shivraj Singh Chouhan]], the former Chief Minister of Madhya Pradesh.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hindu.com/2008/12/13/stories/2008121354440500.htm |title=Other States / Madhya Pradesh News : Shivraj Singh Chouhan sworn in |date=13 December 2008 |work=The Hindu|location=Chennai, India |accessdate=4 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn many villages across [[India]], ''Dharma Raksha Samitis'' (Duty/Religion Protection Committees) promote religious discourse and form an arena for [[bhajan]] performance. The Sangh sponsors calendars of Hindu deities and provides instruction on sanctioned methods of conducting [[Ganesh Chaturthi]] and [[Navaratri]].<ref>{{harvnb|de la Cadena|Starn|2007|p=284}}</ref>\n\n===Deendayal Research Institute===\n{{main|Litigation Free Model}}\nVeteran RSS leader [[Nanaji Deshmukh]] retired from politics at the peak of his political career in 1977 and founded the Deendayal Research Institute, dedicated to building a rural based economic model of development.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chitrakoot.org/html/aboutus.htm |title=Nanaji Deshmukh |website=www.chitrakoot.org}}</ref> It was found that rural people were wasting a lot of resources in litigations, which left them both impoverished and exploited.<ref>Deshmukh said \"If people fight amongst each other, they will have no time for development.\" [http://www.sanghparivar.org/nanaji-deshmukh-a-social-entrepreneur-par-excellence Nanaji Deshmukh: a social entrepreneur par excellence]</ref> Deshmukh and the Institute developed a method of sorting conflicts and differences based on the ancient Indian principles of consensus making and alternate conflict resolution, which has been called the Litigation-Free Model. Based on this model, villagers would sort all disputes amongst themselves amicably with least dependence on the Government.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chitrakoot.org/html/litigation.htm |title=Self Reliance Methodology - Litigation free villages |website=www.chitrakoot.org}}</ref> The initiative has been highly praised, e.g. by Former President [[A. P. J. Abdul Kalam|A.P.J. Abdul Kalam]].{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\nProminent industrialist, [[Jehangir Wadia]], the grandson of [[Muhammad Ali Jinnah]], is influenced by the work of Sangh organisation, Deen Dayal Research Institute (DRI), and is now a volunteer of the DRI. He says \"At 26, I realised that while I was seeking responses to my questions, the answer was always in front of me. That's when I joined Nanaji and got involved in social work at Chitrakoot,\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/money/2005/jun/21spec.htm |title=Wadia's Go Air to offer lowest airfares |work=rediff.com}}</ref> \"Nanaji (founder of DRI) envisions self reliance for 600,000 villages in his life time. It is my dream to translate Nanaji's vision of ameliorating the lives of this rural population.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2006/01/22/stories/2006012200330500.htm |title=High flying chief |work=The Hindu |date=22 January 2006 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061116233058/http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/mag/2006/01/22/stories/2006012200330500.htm |archive-date=16 November 2006 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Politics===\nThe Bharatiya Janata Party, which represents the Sangh Parivar in national politics, has formed three governments in India, most recently being in power from May 2014 under the leadership of [[Indian Prime minister|Prime minister]] [[Narendra Modi]], reelected in May [[2019 Indian general election|2019]].\n\nPolitical opponents of the BJP allege that the party's moderate face merely serves to cover the Sangh Parivar's \"hidden agenda\" of undiluted ''Hindutva'', detectable by the BJP's efforts to change the content of history textbooks and [[syllabus|syllabi]] as well as other aspects of the education system.<ref>{{harvnb|Thakurta|Raghuraman|2004 |loc=[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ur6GAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA64 p.&nbsp;64]}}</ref>\n\nSuch criticism of the BJP arises from the fact that BJP had only 2 seats in the parliament in 1984 and after the Babri Masjid demolition in 1992 the party gained national recognition, and only then it rose to power in 1998.<ref>[[BJP#History]]</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ndtv.com/news/india/babri_masjid_bjp_top_rung_indicted.php |title=Babri Masjid demolition just an incident, says Supreme Court |publisher=Ndtv.com |date=16 January 2012 |accessdate=9 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Matt |url=http://www.law.harvard.edu/students/orgs/hrj/iss16/narula.shtml |title=Harvard Law School Human Rights Journal &#124; |publisher=Law.harvard.edu |accessdate=9 August 2014}}</ref><ref>Book \u2013 Communalism and Secularism in Indian Politics : Study of the BJP</ref>{{full citation needed|date=March 2014}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://countrystudies.us/india/113.htm |title=India \u2013 The Bharatiya Janata Party and the Rise of Hindu Nationalism |publisher=Countrystudies.us |date=7 October 1947 |accessdate=31 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Ayodhya-central-to-BJPs-rise-fall-at-Centre-UP/articleshow/6660668.cms |work=The Times of India |title=Ayodhya central to BJP's rise & fall at Centre, UP |date=1 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Babri Mosque demolition===\nAccording to the report of the [[United Progressive Alliance|UPA]] instituted [[Liberhan Commission]] the Sangh Parivar organised the [[Babri Mosque#Demolition|destruction of the Babri Masjid]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/rssfeed/india/Excerpts-from-the-Liberhan-Commission-report/Article1-479907.aspx |title=Excerpts from the Liberhan Commission report |work=Hindustan Times|date=25 November 2009 |accessdate=26 January 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606125658/http://www.hindustantimes.com/rssfeed/india/Excerpts-from-the-Liberhan-Commission-report/Article1-479907.aspx |archivedate=6 June 2011 |df=dmy}}</ref><ref name=\"indianexpress kar sevaks\">{{cite web |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/how-the-bjp-rss-mobilised-kar-sevaks/545911/ |title=How the BJP, RSS mobilised kar sevaks |work=Indianexpress|date=25 November 2009 |accessdate=26 January 2011}}</ref> The Commission said- \"The blame or the credit for the entire temple construction movement at Ayodhya must necessarily be attributed to the Sangh Parivar\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.rediff.com/report/2009/nov/24/liberhan-comes-down-heavily-on-advani-and-vajpayee.htm |title=Liberhan comes down heavily on Vajpayee, Advani \u2013 Rediff.com India News |publisher=News.rediff.com |date=24 November 2009 |accessdate=26 January 2011}}</ref>\n\nIt also noted that the Sangh Parivar is an \"extensive and widespread organic body\", which encompasses organizations, which address and bring together just about every type of social, professional and other demographic grouping of individuals.\n{{bq|1=Each time, a new demographic group has emerged, the Sangh Parivar has hived off some of its RSS inner-core leadership to harness that group and bring it within the fold, enhancing the voter base of the Parivar.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report_vajpayee-advani-severely-indicted-by-liberhan-commission_1315927 |title=Vajpayee, Advani severely indicted by Liberhan Commission \u2013 India \u2013 DNA |publisher=Dnaindia.com |date=24 November 2009 |accessdate=26 January 2011}}</ref>}}\n\n==Sangh Parivar members==\nThe Sangh Parivar includes the following organisations (with membership figures in brackets). They are also categorized.\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n;Political\n* [[Jammu Praja Parishad|All Jammu and Kashmir Praja Parishad]], literally, \"People's Council\", a political party active in [[Jammu Division|Jammu]] from 1947 to 1963.\n* [[Bharatiya Jana Sangh]], literally, \"Indian People's Association\" a political party that existed from 1951 to 1977.\n* [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] (BJP), ''Indian People's Party'' (150 million, August 2019)<ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Narendra-Modi-heaps-praise-on-Amit-Shah-as-BJP-membership-touches-10-crore/articleshow/46790420.cms Narendra Modi heaps praise on Amit Shah as BJP membership touches 10 crore], Times of India, 3 April 2015.</ref>\n\n;Occupational and Professional\n* [[Bharatiya Kisan Sangh]], literally, ''Indian Farmers' Association'' (8m){{sfn|Jelen|2002|p=253}}\n* [[Bharatiya Mazdoor Sangh]], ''Indian Labourers' Association'' (10 million as of 2009){{sfn|Jelen|2002|p=253}}\n* Bharatiya Railways Sangh, ''Indian Railways Workers' Association''\n* Fishermen's Co-operative Societies (2.2m){{sfn|Jelen|2002|p=253}}\n* Samskar Bharati, ''Organisation of Indian Artists''{{sfn|Chitkara|2004|p=168}}\n* [[Akhil Bharatiya Adhivakta Parishad]], ''All India Lawyers' Council''{{sfn|Jaffrelot|2011|p=204}}\n* [[Akhil Bharatiya Vidyarthi Parishad]], ''All India Students' Council'' (2.8m){{sfn|Jelen|2002|p=253}}\n* Akhil Bharatiya Shaikshik Mahasangh, ''All India Teachers' Federation'' (1.8m){{sfn|Jelen|2002|p=253}}\n* National Medicos Organisation, ''Organisation of Medical Practitioners''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/nepal-earthquake-rss-relief-work-kathmandu-hindu-swayamsevak-sangh/1/432672.html |title=Nepal earthquake: RSS rolls out relief |work=intoday.in}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://nmoindia.com/ |title=Home |author=Shoolin Design Pvt. Ltd. |work=nmoindia.com}}</ref>\n* Akhil Bharatiya Poorva Sainik Seva Parishad, (ABPSSP) ''All India Ex-Military Servicemen Council.''<ref name=\"mangalorean.com\">{{cite news |title=ABPS session begins in Puttur RSS leaders to focus on Corruption |date=12 March 2011 |publisher=Mangalore Media Company |url=http://www.mangalorean.com/news.php?newstype=broadcast&broadcastid=227040 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402144440/http://www.mangalorean.com/news.php?newstype=broadcast&broadcastid=227040 |archivedate=2 April 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"samvada.org\">{{Cite news |title=RSS top 3day Annual meet Akhil Bharatiya Pratinidhi Sabha (ABPS), to be held on March 7\u20139 at Bangalore |date=3 March 2014 |publisher=Vishwa Samvada Kendra |url=http://samvada.org/2014/news/rss-top-3day-annual-meet-akhil-bharatiya-pratinidhi-sabha-abps-to-be-held-on-march-7-9-at-bangalore/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140306184618/http://samvada.org/2014/news/rss-top-3day-annual-meet-akhil-bharatiya-pratinidhi-sabha-abps-to-be-held-on-march-7-9-at-bangalore |archivedate=6 March 2014 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=About Us |publisher=Akhil Bharatiya Poorva Sainik Seva Parishad |url=http://www.abpssp.org/about-us.php |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150202180227/http://abpssp.org/about-us.php |archivedate=2 February 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n;Economic\n* [[Swadeshi Jagaran Manch]], ''Nativist Awakening Front''{{sfn|Chitkara|2004|p=169}}\n* Vitta Salahkar Parishad, ''Financial consultants' association''\n* Laghu Udyog Bharati, ''an extensive network of small industries.''<ref>\"Laghu Udyog Bharati\" {{Cite news |title=Ministers, not group, to scan scams |date=1 October 2004 |newspaper=The Telegraph |location=Calcutta, India |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1041001/asp/nation/story_3826950.asp |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924123634/http://www.telegraphindia.com/1041001/asp/nation/story_3826950.asp |archivedate=24 September 2015 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>\"Laghu Udyog Bharati\" {{Cite news |author=Jaffrelot. Christophe |date=1 December 2014 |title=Parivar\u2019s diversity in unity |newspaper=The Indian Express |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/editorials/parivars-diversity-in-unity/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.o