{"title_page": "List of Bleach video games", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:List of ''Bleach'' video games}}\n{{featured list}}\n[[File:BleachAnimeLogo.jpg|300px|right|thumb|alt=The word \"BLEACH\" is in red block letters with blue outlines. Below it are two horizontal lines interrupted in the middle by various typographical characters. On either side of the word are blue outlines of flames.|The logo of the ''Bleach'' series as seen on all of the video game covers]]There are several [[video game]]s based on [[Tite Kubo]]'s manga and anime series ''[[Bleach (manga)|Bleach]]''. The titles consist mostly of [[Side-scrolling video game|side-scrolling]] [[Fighting game|fighters]], but also include other genres such as [[Tactical role-playing game|strategy role-playing games]] and [[action role-playing game]]s. Most of the games retell the [[Bleach (manga)#Plot|plot]] of the manga, following [[Ichigo Kurosaki]] and [[List of Bleach characters|his friends]]. Some games, however, have veered from the source material and incorporated original stories and characters. The games have been released on a variety of [[video game console|home]] and [[handheld game console|handheld consoles]].\n\nThe first game to be released based on the ''Bleach'' series was ''[[Bleach: Heat the Soul (series)#Bleach: Heat the Soul|Bleach: Heat the Soul]]'', which debuted on March 24, 2005, and the latest releases are ''[[Bleach: Soul Resurrecci\u00f3n]]'', which was released in North America on August 2, 2011 and ''Bleach: Bankai Batoru'', a [[Social network game|social network]] game which was released in Japan on April 14, 2014.<ref name=\"HTSRelease\"/><ref name=\"Ignition\"/><ref name=\"Bankai Battle\"/> There are 23 games bearing the \"''Bleach''\" name, not including the four [[Fictional crossover|crossover]] games\u2014''[[Jump Super Stars]]'', ''[[Jump Ultimate Stars]]'', ''[[J-Stars Victory VS]]'' and ''[[Jump Force]]''\u2014which feature characters from numerous other ''[[Weekly Sh\u014dnen Jump]]'' anime and manga series. Most ''Bleach'' games have been released only in Japan, though [[Sega]] has localized the first [[Wii]] game and the first three [[Nintendo DS]] games for North America, Australia, and Europe. Reception toward the games has been mixed, ranging from \"the best fighter\" for ''[[Bleach: The Blade of Fate]]'', to \"(not) a bad first effort, but the competition is leaving this one in the dust\" for ''[[Bleach: Shattered Blade]]''.<ref name=\"FateReview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2007/10/09/bleach-the-blade-of-fate-review|title=IGN: ''Bleach: The Blade of Fate Review''|author=Bozon|publisher=[[IGN]]|date=October 8, 2007|accessdate=May 30, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"BladeReview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2007/10/23/bleach-shattered-blade-review|title=IGN: ''Bleach: Shattered Blade Review''|author=Bozon|publisher=[[IGN]]|date=October 23, 2007|accessdate=May 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Series==\n\n===''Bleach: Blade Battlers''===\n{{main|Bleach: Blade Battlers (series)}}\nThe {{Nihongo|''Bleach: Blade Battlers''|Bleach\u301c\u30d6\u30ec\u30a4\u30c9\u30fb\u30d0\u30c8\u30e9\u30fc\u30ba\u301c}} series is a series of [[3D computer graphics|3-D]] [[Cel shading|cel-shaded]] [[fighting game]]s developed by [[Racjin]] and published by [[SCEI]].\n{{Video game titles|\n{{Video game titles/item\n|title=Bleach: Blade Battlers\n|date={{vgrelease|JP|October 12, 2006}}\n|refs=<ref name=\"BladeBattlers\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jp.playstation.com/software/title/scps15116.html|title=Bleach \u301c\u30d6\u30ec\u30a4\u30c9\u30fb\u30d0\u30c8\u30e9\u30fc\u30ba\u301c|publisher=[[PlayStation]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 27, 2014}}</ref>\n|release=2006\u2014[[PlayStation 2]]<ref name=\"BladeBattlers\"/>\n|notes=* Features 4-player versus mode<ref name=\"BladeBattlers\"/>\n* Released under ''[[The Best (PlayStation range)|The Best]]'' label on October 25, 2007 in Japan<ref name=\"BladeBattlersRR\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jp.playstation.com/software/title/scps19329.html|title=Bleach \u301c\u30d6\u30ec\u30a4\u30c9\u30fb\u30d0\u30c8\u30e9\u30fc\u30ba\u301c PlayStation\u00ae2 the Best|publisher=[[PlayStation]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 27, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Video game titles/item\n|title=Bleach: Blade Battlers 2nd\n|date={{vgrelease|JP|September 27, 2007}}\n|refs=<ref name=\"BladeBattlers2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jp.playstation.com/software/title/scps15119.html|title=Bleach \u301c\u30d6\u30ec\u30a4\u30c9\u30fb\u30d0\u30c8\u30e9\u30fc\u30ba2nd\u301c|publisher=[[PlayStation]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 27, 2014}}</ref>\n|release=2007\u2014PlayStation 2<ref name=\"BladeBattlers2\"/>\n|notes=* Features 36 playable characters<ref name=\"BladeBattlers2PixFans\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pixfans.com/analisis-de-bleach-blade-battlers-2nd/|author=Amorin Uzuki|title=An\u00e1lisis de Bleach Blade Battlers 2nd|date=October 4, 2007|publisher=pixfans.com|language=Spanish|accessdate=August 14, 2014}}</ref>\n* The game features 4-player cooperative and versus modes<ref name=\"BladeBattlers2PixFans\"/>\n}}\n}}\n\n===''Bleach DS''===\nThe ''Bleach DS'' series are [[2D computer graphics|2-D]] games. The first two were fighting games developed by [[Treasure (company)|Treasure Co. Ltd]]. All four were published by [[Sega]].\n\n{{Video game titles|\n{{Video game titles/item\n|title=Bleach: The Blade of Fate\n|article=Bleach: The Blade of Fate\n|date={{vgrelease|JP|January 26, 2006}}{{vgrelease|NA|October 9, 2007}}{{vgrelease|AUS|February 28, 2008}}{{vgrelease|EU|February 29, 2008}}\n|refs=<ref name=\"JPFateRelease\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ds/software/ablj/index.html|title=Bleach DS\u3000\u84bc\u5929\u306b\u99c6\u3051\u308b\u904b\u547d |publisher=[[Nintendo]]|language=Japanese|accessdate=May 28, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"USFateRelease\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/games/bleach-the-blade-of-fate/nds-763827|title=Bleach: The Blade o