ences==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.jp.playstation.com/scej/title/bleach/ Official PlayStation ''Bleach'' website] {{in lang|ja}}\n* [http://www.8ing.net/ Official Fighting website] {{in lang|ja}}\n\n{{Bleach games}}\n\n[[Category:Bleach games| ]]\n[[Category:Shueisha franchises|Bleach video games]]\n[[Category:Video game lists by franchise|Bleach]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "punct", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Bleach_video_games"}
{"title_page": "1974 Greek legislative election", "text_new": "{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 1974 Greek legislative election\n| country = Greece\n| type = parliamentary\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = Greek_legislative_election, 1964\n| previous_year = 1964\n| previous_mps = Greek legislative election, 1964\n| next_election = 1977 Greek legislative election\n| next_year = 1977\n| next_mps = Greek_legislative_election, 1977\n| seats_for_election = All 300 seats to the [[Greek Parliament]] <br /> 151 seats were needed for a majority\n| election_date = 17 November 1974\n\n<!--      Conservative      -->\n| image1 = [[File:KaramanlisNatsinasAgora crop.jpg|110px]]\n| leader1 = [[Konstantinos Karamanlis]]\n| leader_since1 = 4 October 1974\n| party1 = New Democracy (Greece)\n| leaders_seat1 = \n| last_election1 = ''New''\n| seats1 = 220\n| seat_change1 = ''New''\n| popular_vote1 = 2,669,133\n| percentage1 = 54.37%\n| swing1 = ''New''\n\n<!--      Socialist     -->\n| image4 = [[File:Andreas Papandreou.jpg|105px]]\n| leader4 = [[Andreas Papandreou]]\n| leader_since4 = 3 September 1974\n| party4 = Panhellenic Socialist Movement\n| leaders_seat4 =\n| last_election4 = ''New''\n| seats4 = 12\n| seat_change4 = ''New''\n| popular_vote4 = 666,413\n| percentage4 = 13.58%\n| swing4 = ''New''\n\n<!--      Liberal      -->\n| image2 = [[File:GEORGIOS MAVROS.jpg|128px]]\n| leader2 = [[Georgios Mavros]]\n| leader_since2 = 1974\n| party2 = Center Union-New Forces\n| leaders_seat2 =\n| last_election2 = 171 seats, 52.72%\n| seats2 = 60\n| seat_change2 = {{decrease}} 111\n| popular_vote2 = 1,002,559\n| percentage2 = 20.42%\n| swing2 = {{decrease}} 32.3%\n\n| image5 = [[File:No image.png|105px]]\n| leader5 = [[Ilias Iliou]]\n| leader_since5 = 3 September 1974\n| party5 = [[United Left (Greece)|EA]]\n| leaders_seat5 =\n| last_election5 = ''New''\n| seats5 = 8\n| seat_change5 = ''New''\n| popular_vote5 = 464,787\n| percentage5 = 9.47%\n| swing5 = ''New''\n| color5 = FF0000\n\n| title = [[Prime Minister of Greece|Prime Minister]]\n| posttitle = Subsequent Prime Minister\n| before_election = [[Konstantinos Karamanlis]]\n| before_party = New Democracy (Greece)\n| after_election = [[Konstantinos Karamanlis]]\n| after_party = New Democracy (Greece)\n}}\n'''Parliamentary elections''' were held in [[Greece]] on 17 November 1974.<ref name=NS>[[Dieter Nohlen]] & Philip St\u00f6ver (2010) ''Elections in Europe: A data handbook'', p830 {{ISBN|978-3-8329-5609-7}}</ref> They were the first after the end of the [[Greek military junta of 1967\u20131974]] and took place during the [[metapolitefsi]] era. The winner was [[Konstantinos Karamanlis]] and his newly formed conservative party, [[New Democracy (Greece)|ND]] (''New Democracy, \u039d\u03ad\u03b1 \u0394\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03ba\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03af\u03b1''). Karamanlis had already formed a government of national unity just after the fall of the dictatorship. The second biggest party was the centrist [[Center Union - New Forces]] (''\u0388\u03bd\u03c9\u03c3\u03b9\u03c2 \u039a\u03ad\u03bd\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5-\u039d\u03ad\u03b5\u03c2 \u0394\u03c5\u03bd\u03ac\u03bc\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2''). Third power in the Parliament became the newly formed [[Panhellenic Socialist Movement|PASOK]] (''Panhellenic Socialist Movement, \u03a0\u03b1\u03bd\u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03ae\u03bd\u03b9\u03bf \u03a3\u03bf\u03c3\u03b9\u03b1\u03bb\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u039a\u03af\u03bd\u03b7\u03bc\u03b1''), a radical socialist party led by [[Andreas Papandreou]], son of the former prime minister [[George Papandreou, senior|Georgios Papandreou]].\n\n==Results==\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:right\n!Party\n!Votes\n!%\n!Seats\n|-\n|align=left|[[New Democracy (Greece)|New Democracy]] (ND)||2,669,133||54.4||220\n|-\n|align=left|[[Centre Union \u2013 New Forces]] (EK-ND)||1,002,559||20.4||60\n|-\n|align=left|[[Panhellenic Socialist Movement]] (PASOK)||666,413||13.6||12\n|-\n|align=left|[[United Left (Greece)|United Left]] (EA)||464,787||9.5||8\n|-\n|align=left|[[National Democratic Union (Greece)|National Democratic Union]] (EDE)||52,768||1.1||0\n|-\n|align=left|[[Democratic Centre Union (Greece)|Democratic Centre Union]] (DEK)||8,509||0.2||0\n|-\n|align=left|[[Revolutionary Communist Movement of Greece]] (EKKE)||1,599||0.0||0\n|-\n|align=left|Coalition [[Liberal Democratic Union (Greece)|Liberal Democratic Union]]-[[Socialist Party of Greece]] (FDE-SKE)||975||0.0||0\n|-\n|align=left|[[List of Independents]] and independents||42,291||0.9||0\n|-\n|align=left|Invalid/blank votes||54,584||\u2013||\u2013\n|-\n|align=left|'''Total'''||'''4,963,558'''||'''100'''||'''300'''\n|-\n|align=left|Registered voters/turnout||6,241,066||79.5||\u2013\n|-\n|align=left colspan=4|Source: Nohlen & St\u00f6ver\n|}\n\n{{Bar box\n|title=Popular vote\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|width=600px\n|barwidth=350px\n|bars=\n{{Bar percent|ND|{{New Democracy (Greece)/meta/color}}|54.37}}\n{{Bar percent|EK-ND|{{Center Union-New Forces/meta/color}}|20.42}}\n{{Bar percent|PASOK|{{Panhellenic Socialist Movement/meta/color}}|13.58}}\n{{Bar percent|EA|{{Communist Party of Greece/meta/color}}|9.47}}\n{{Bar percent|EDE|#000000|1.08}}\n{{Bar percent|Others|{{Other/meta/color}}|1.09}}\n}}\n\n{{Bar box\n|title=Parliament seats\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|width=600px\n|barwidth=350px\n|bars=\n{{Bar percent|ND|{{New Democracy (Greece)/meta/color}}|73.33}}\n{{Bar percent|EK-ND|{{Center Union-New Forces/meta/color}}|20.00}}\n{{Bar percent|PASOK|{{Panhellenic Socialist Movement/meta/color}}|4.00}}\n{{Bar percent|EA|{{Communist Party of Greece/meta/color}}|2.67}}\n}}\n{{legend|#FF0000|EA: 8 seats}} {{legend|#035E0C|PASOK: 12 seats}} {{legend|#C9A77F|EK-ND: 60 seats}} {{legend|#0E00CE|ND: 220 seats}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe priorities of the Karamanlis' government were:\n*The adoption of a new Constitution\n*The abolition of Monarchy after a free referendum\n*The submission of a new application for Greece's accession to the European Community.\n\nThe new government decided to hold [[1974 Greek republic referendum|a referendum on retaining the republic]]. It was held on 8 December 1974.\n\nIn 1975 [[Constantine Tsatsos|Konstantinos Tsatsos]], a close friend of Karamanlis, was elected [[List of Presidents of Greece|President of the Republic]] by the [[Greek Parliament]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal |last=Tridimas |first=George |title=Referendum and the choice between monarchy and republic in Greece |journal=Constitutional Political Economy |volume=21 |issue=2 |year=2010 |pages=119\u2013144 |doi=10.1007/s10602-009-9078-4 }}\n\n{{Greek elections}}\n\n[[Category:Parliamentary elections in Greece|1974]]\n[[Category:1974 in Greece|Legislative election]]\n[[Category:1970s in Greek politics]]\n[[Category:1974 elections in Europe]]\n[[Category:November 1974 events in Europe]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 1974 Greek legislative election\n| country = Greece\n| type = parliamentary\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = Greek_legislative_election, 1964\n| previous_year = 1964\n| previous_mps = Greek legislative election, 1964\n| next_election = 1977 Greek legislative election\n| next_year = 1977\n| next_mps = Greek_legislative_election, 1977\n| seats_for_election = All 300 seats to the [[Greek Parliament]] <br /> 151 seats were needed for a majority\n| election_date = 17 November 1974\n\n<!--      Conservative      -->\n| image1 = [[File:KaramanlisNatsinasAgora crop.jpg|110px]]\n| leader1 = [[Konstantinos Karamanlis]]\n| leader_since1 = 4 October 1974\n| party1 = New Democracy (Greece)\n| leaders_seat1 = \n| last_election1 = ''New''\n| seats1 = 220\n| seat_change1 = ''New''\n| popular_vote1 = 2,669,133\n| percentage1 = 54.37%\n| swing1 = ''New''\n\n<!--      Socialist     -->\n| image4 = [[File:Andreas Papandreou.jpg|105px]]\n| leader4 = [[Andreas Papandreou]]\n| leader_since4 = 3 September 1974\n| party4 = Panhellenic Socialist Movement\n| leaders_seat4 =\n| last_election4 = ''New''\n| seats4 = 12\n| seat_change4 = ''New''\n| popular_vote4 = 666,413\n| percentage4 = 13.58%\n| swing4 = ''New''\n\n<!--      Liberal      -->\n| image2 = [[File:GEORGIOS MAVROS.jpg|128px]]\n| leader2 = [[Georgios Mavros]]\n| leader_since2 = 1974\n| party2 = Center Union-New Forces\n| leaders_seat2 =\n| last_election2 = 171 seats, 52.72%\n| seats2 = 60\n| seat_change2 = {{decrease}} 111\n| popular_vote2 = 1,002,559\n| percentage2 = 20.42%\n| swing2 = {{decrease}} 32.3%\n\n| image5 = [[File:No image.png|105px]]\n| leader5 = [[Ilias Iliou]]\n| leader_since5 = 3 September 1974\n| party5 = [[United Left (Greece)|EA]]\n| leaders_seat5 =\n| last_election5 = ''New''\n| seats5 = 8\n| seat_change5 = ''New''\n| popular_vote5 = 464,787\n| percentage5 = 9.47%\n| swing5 = ''New''\n| color5 = FF0000\n\n| title = [[Prime Minister of Greece|Prime Minister]]\n| posttitle = Subsequent Prime Minister\n| before_election = [[Konstantinos Karamanlis]]\n| before_party = New Democracy (Greece)\n| after_election = [[Konstantinos Karamanlis]]\n| after_party = New Democracy (Greece)\n}}\n'''Parliamentary elections''' were held in [[Greece]] on 17 November 1974.<ref name=NS>[[Dieter Nohlen]] & Philip St\u00f6ver (2010) ''Elections in Europe: A data handbook'', p830 {{ISBN|978-3-8329-5609-7}}</ref> They were the first after the end of the [[Greek military junta of 1967\u20131974]] and took place during the [[metapolitefsi]] era. The winner was [[Konstantinos Karamanlis]] and his newly formed conservative party, [[New Democracy (Greece)|ND]] (''New Democracy, \u039d\u03ad\u03b1 \u0394\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03ba\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03af\u03b1''). Karamanlis had already formed a government of national unity just after the fall of the dictatorship. The second biggest party was the centrist [[Center Union - New Forces]] (''\u0388\u03bd\u03c9\u03c3\u03b9\u03c2 \u039a\u03ad\u03bd\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5-\u039d\u03ad\u03b5\u03c2 \u0394\u03c5\u03bd\u03ac\u03bc\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2''). Third power in the Parliament became the newly formed [[Panhellenic Socialist Movement|PASOK]] (''Panhellenic Sosialist Movement, \u03a0\u03b1\u03bd\u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03ae\u03bd\u03b9\u03bf \u03a3\u03bf\u03c3\u03b9\u03b1\u03bb\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u039a\u03af\u03bd\u03b7\u03bc\u03b1''), a radical socialist party led by [[Andreas Papandreou]], son of the former prime minister [[George Papandreou, senior|Georgios Papandreou]].\n\n==Results==\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:right\n!Party\n!Votes\n!%\n!Seats\n|-\n|align=left|[[New Democracy (Greece)|New Democracy]] (ND)||2,669,133||54.4||220\n|-\n|align=left|[[Centre Union \u2013 New Forces]] (EK-ND)||1,002,559||20.4||60\n|-\n|align=left|[[Panhellenic Socialist Movement]] (PASOK)||666,413||13.6||12\n|-\n|align=left|[[United Left (Greece)|United Left]] (EA)||464,787||9.5||8\n|-\n|align=left|[[National Democratic Union (Greece)|National Democratic Union]] (EDE)||52,768||1.1||0\n|-\n|align=left|[[Democratic Centre Union (Greece)|Democratic Centre Union]] (DEK)||8,509||0.2||0\n|-\n|align=left|[[Revolutionary Communist Movement of Greece]] (EKKE)||1,599||0.0||0\n|-\n|align=left|Coalition [[Liberal Democratic Union (Greece)|Liberal Democratic Union]]-[[Socialist Party of Greece]] (FDE-SKE)||975||0.0||0\n|-\n|align=left|[[List of Independents]] and independents||42,291||0.9||0\n|-\n|align=left|Invalid/blank votes||54,584||\u2013||\u2013\n|-\n|align=left|'''Total'''||'''4,963,558'''||'''100'''||'''300'''\n|-\n|align=left|Registered voters/turnout||6,241,066||79.5||\u2013\n|-\n|align=left colspan=4|Source: Nohlen & St\u00f6ver\n|}\n\n{{Bar box\n|title=Popular vote\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|width=600px\n|barwidth=350px\n|bars=\n{{Bar percent|ND|{{New Democracy (Greece)/meta/color}}|54.37}}\n{{Bar percent|EK-ND|{{Center Union-New Forces/meta/color}}|20.42}}\n{{Bar percent|PASOK|{{Panhellenic Socialist Movement/meta/color}}|13.58}}\n{{Bar percent|EA|{{Communist Party of Greece/meta/color}}|9.47}}\n{{Bar percent|EDE|#000000|1.08}}\n{{Bar percent|Others|{{Other/meta/color}}|1.09}}\n}}\n\n{{Bar box\n|title=Parliament seats\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|width=600px\n|barwidth=350px\n|bars=\n{{Bar percent|ND|{{New Democracy (Greece)/meta/color}}|73.33}}\n{{Bar percent|EK-ND|{{Center Union-New Forces/meta/color}}|20.00}}\n{{Bar percent|PASOK|{{Panhellenic Socialist Movement/meta/color}}|4.00}}\n{{Bar percent|EA|{{Communist Party of Greece/meta/color}}|2.67}}\n}}\n{{legend|#FF0000|EA: 8 seats}} {{legend|#035E0C|PASOK: 12 seats}} {{legend|#C9A77F|EK-ND: 60 seats}} {{legend|#0E00CE|ND: 220 seats}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe priorities of the Karamanlis' government were:\n*The adoption of a new Constitution\n*The abolition of Monarchy after a free referendum\n*The submission of a new application for Greece's accession to the European Community.\n\nThe new government decided to hold [[1974 Greek republic referendum|a referendum on retaining the republic]]. It was held on 8 December 1974.\n\nIn 1975 [[Constantine Tsatsos|Konstantinos Tsatsos]], a close friend of Karamanlis, was elected [[List of Presidents of Greece|President of the Republic]] by the [[Greek Parliament]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite journal |last=Tridimas |first=George |title=Referendum and the choice between monarchy and republic in Greece |journal=Constitutional Political Economy |volume=21 |issue=2 |year=2010 |pages=119\u2013144 |doi=10.1007/s10602-009-9078-4 }}\n\n{{Greek elections}}\n\n[[Category:Parliamentary elections in Greece|1974]]\n[[Category:1974 in Greece|Legislative election]]\n[[Category:1970s in Greek politics]]\n[[Category:1974 elections in Europe]]\n[[Category:November 1974 events in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1974_Greek_legislative_election"}
